<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-36 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Dissatisfied With Mozambique's Taxation On Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maputo, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
today expressed dissatisfaction at Mozambique's decision to
impose levy on its food aid to millions of the country's needy.
</P>
<P>
Philip Clarck, the WFP representative in Maputo, said he
could not understand why the Mozambican government made the
decision in December last year.
</P>
<P>
The WFP had enjoyed exemption from taxation since it started
emergency food aid operations in Mozambique in 1992, according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of tax exemption is also imposed on other
United Nations aid agencies as well as non-governmental
organizations, which are working for the survival of famine
victims in the southern African nation, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican Customs Office recently held 4,000 tons of
maize imported by WFP from South Africa, ordering a tax payment
at 300 U.S. dollars for each ton, Clarck revealed, adding the
impounded maize was intended for 350,000 refugees in southern
Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
