<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Urges Turkish Cypriots to Join Efforts for a Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides has urged the Turkish Cypriots to join efforts for a
solution to the Cyprus problem before the island's accession to
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Turkish Cypriot daily Kibris published
today, the President said, "The prospect of joining the EU offers
a great opportunity to all the people of Cyprus and it is an
opportunity that both Greek-Cypriots and Turkish-Cypriots should
not miss."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots should hurry up so that a solution to the
Cyprus problem is reached before talks for the island's accession
to the EU start six months after the conclusion of the 1996 EU
Intergovernmental Conference, the President said.
</P>
<P>
"We will then be able to negotiate together our accession to
the EU," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his proposal on an "acceptable" security in a
future federated Cyprus for both sides, the President proposed
new guarantors to be added in the list of the old ones, namely
Greece, Turkey and Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Thus the independence, territorial integrity and
constitutional order of the Republic will be guaranteed by a
greater number of guarantors," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
"An international force made up from contingents of the
guarantors will be stationed in a demilitarized Cyprus," he
added.
</P>
<P>
This force, according to the President, will ensure that no
paramilitary organization is created in Cyprus and intervene
after a guarantors' decision taken by majority in specific cases.
</P>
<P>
The President stressed that "since we wish to join the EU the
guarantors should be from the EU and other countries."
</P>
<P>
On the territorial aspect, the President said it should be
solved in such a way that it would allow at least two thirds of
the refugees to go back to their homes under Greek Cypriot
administration.
</P>
<P>
"The remaining refugees who may decide to go back under
Turkish Cypriot administration will not affect the substantial
Turkish Cypriot majority in the area. Greek and Turkish Cypriots
who will choose not to return will have the option to sell,
exchange or retain their properties," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of sovereignty, Clerides said that a federal
Cyprus Republic should have "a single, indivisible, international,
legal personality and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"However, all powers and functions of the federal state and of
the two federated cantons will be derived and will flow from the
constitution of the federal Republic.
</P>
<P>
"The powers for the federated cantons, which will have a
maximum degree of autonomy in internal administration, will be
agreed upon," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the question of political equality, the President
said the status of both communities has been defined by
U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali in his report of 30
April, 1992, paragraph II, which refers to "not equal numerical
participation but effective participation of both communities in
the federal government." "This definition is acceptable to our
side," Clerides added.
</P>
<P>
The President proposed that all political leaders, including
himself and Rauf Denktash, "should make a joint declaration that
never again our communities shall raise arms against each other."
</P>
<P>
He maintained that a Cyprus settlement could be reached "very
rapidly" provided there is political will to solve the problem
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriot north and
Greek Cypriot south since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island following a short-lived
coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
