<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers Continue All-Russian Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 230,000 teachers today
continue their nationwide strike, demanding their unpaid wages,
according to media reports here.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which began on Tuesday, led to closure of more than
4,000 schools in more than two-thirds of Russian regions.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Tribune daily cited a spokeswoman for the All-Russia
Union of Science and Education workers as saying that more than 50
regions were planning to take part in the strike protest action.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin has responded to the strike by blaming
"lack of organization in the relevant structures and bureaucrats"
for the salary delays, the Interfax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
He promised to set up a special reserve fund in March to
prevent future delays in paying out wages in state enterprises and
public services.
</P>
<P>
The strike comes amidst growing malaise in Russia's labor
force, with a massive coal miners' strike going on in the country.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass reported that about 87 percent of the country's coal
mining enterprises have been paralyzed after 500,000 miners staged
a nationwide strike to protest months of unpaid slaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
