<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Officials Sued on Foster Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. federal prosecutors
accused New York City and state officials Wednesday of defrauding
the federal government out of tens of millions of dollars by
falsely reporting that services were delivered to thousands of
children in foster care, the New York Time reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a lawsuit filed in Federal District Court in Manhattan, the
government said that from 1990 to 1994, the city's Child Welfare
Administration intentionally misled federal officials to obtain
millions of dollars in federal funds by stating that children had
received attention from case-workers when they often had not, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for federal funds, city officials are required to
monitor the care of children in foster homes and file reports on
each case once every six months.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency's staff members were not always conducting
the reviews of foster care cases. Instead, the employees were
ordered by their superiors to file false data saying that they had
conducted the reviews. And the head of the agency and other agency
officials in charge of foster care knew that, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors also accused New York State of receiving 37.4
million dollars in federal foster care funds between 1990 and
1994.
</P>
<P>
The federal government is seeking at least 112 million dollars
in damages from the city and the state as it accused the city and
state of depriving "needy foster children and their families" of
foster services.
</P>
<P>
"The children of this city who are the most vulnerable and in
need of attention have been deprived of critical, federally
mandated foster care services," United States Attorney Mary Jo
White said in announcing the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit comes as the agency is being scrutinized for how it
handled the case of 6-year-old Elisa Izquierdo who died recently
from a severe beating by her mother and other reports of neglects
of child care in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
