<HEADLINE> First Batch of Japanese Peacekeeping Unit Arrives in Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of the
Japanese military unit, due to join the U.N. peacekeeping force in
the Israeli-occupied Syrian Golan Heights, arrived in Damascus
this evening.
</P>
<P>
This batch comprises 14 men of the Japanese Self Defense
Force and two civilians. The second 29-strong Japanese batch is
scheduled to depart Japan on February 7 to take up positions in
the Golan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese force will be replacing a Canadian unit whose
duties in the U.N. peacekeeping force in the Golan has come to an
end.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the Japanese government is dispatching
such a unit to the Middle East. The Japanese parliament had agreed
last December on the planned dispatch of a Japanese peacekeeping
force to serve in the Golan Heights for a period of two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
