<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik President Says Situation Remains Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Tajik President Emomali
Rakhmanov said today that the situation in his country remained
"complex but not out of control," according to reports reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament of Tajikistan, a former Soviet
Republic in the Central Asia, Rakhmonov stressed that "we shall
not let the conflict and provocations grow up."
</P>
<P>
He said that a parliamentary commission set up to handle the
crisis was holding negotiations with two groups of rebels in
Kurgan-Tyube and Tursun-Zade, both cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
One rebel leader, former Tursun-Zade Mayor, and his armed
supporters attacked the city on January 26, demanding the
dismissal of some administration officials and power ministers.
</P>
<P>
Another rebel leader, commander of the 1st rifle brigade
deployed outside Kurgan-Tyube, led his soldiers in attacking the
city one day later, demanding the resignation of the central
government and local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmonov told the lawmakers that talks with the rebels should
be held "in the framework of the constitution and existing
legislation".
</P>
<P>
In another development, the fighting between the government
troops and the opposition units continued today in the Tavil-Dara
region, some 300 kilometers east of Dushanbe
</P>
<P>
Some 300 opposition militants are involved in the on-going
fierce battle in the region bordering on Afghanistan, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Rakhmonov blamed "foreign political forces" for
the current destabilization in the republic," accusing them of
attempts "to wipe the republic off the world map."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Uzbek and Russian Presidents Islam Karimov and
Boris Yeltsin had a telephone talk and decided that "it was
necessary to settle the conflict in Tajikistan by joint efforts."
The situation in Tajikistan evoked "serious concern" of the
Russian President, his spokesman Sergei Medvedev told reporters
here today.
</P>
<P>
Karimov's adviser Bakhtiyer Gulyamov arrived in Dushanbe this
morning. Yuri Baturi, national security adviser to Yeltsin,
arrived there at about the same time. According to the Itar-Tass
news agency, Baturin, accompanied by a group of Russian military
experts, has gone to Kurgan-Tyube to meet rebel leader
Khudoberdiyev, apparently to seek a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Rakhmonov also briefed Yeltsin on the latest
developments in his country in a telephone conversation. The
Russian President reaffirmed his "firm support for President
Rakhmonov's efforts" to stabilize the socio-political situation in
Tajikistan, Rakhmonov's spokesman Zafar Saidov said in Dushanbe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
