<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM to Buy Software Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Business
Machines Corp. (IBM) agreed to pay 743 million U.S. dollars or
47.50 U.S. dollars a share to buy software developer Tivoli
Systems.
</P>
<P>
This will become IBM's second big acquisition in eight months.
Last June, IBM paid a hefty 3.5 billion U.S. dollars to buy Lotus
Development and its flagship Notes software. These two moves are
regarded as an ambition: expand IBM's presence in computer
networking.
</P>
<P>
Lotus's Notes Version 4 is designed to make data publishing and
collecting on Internet much more convenient.
</P>
<P>
Tivoli makes software that helps companies switch from
mainframes to networks of smaller computers.
</P>
<P>
"As more and more customers exploit powerful computer networks
for competitive advantage, the need for systems management
products to operate and maintain those networks becomes critical,"
IBM Chief Executive Louis Gerstner said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Local press here reported that Frank Moss, Tivoli's chief
executive officer, will continue to run the company as an
autonomous unit of IBM. He also will oversee IBM's existing
system-management software, a business that brings in more than 1
billion U.S. dollars a year for the company.
</P>
<P>
The "Wall Street Journal" reported that IBM can well afford
takeovers. Its cash holding stood at 7.7 billion at the end of
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
