<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Short of Funds, to Reduce Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Worsening Financial crisis has
compelled the United Nations to cut back over 1,000 staff in 1996
in order to achieve the planned 10 percent reduction in expenses.
</P>
<P>
The move, released recently at press briefings both at New York
and Geneva, came as result of some countries in arrears with their
contributions to U.N.
</P>
<P>
By mid-January 1996, unpaid dues to UN totalled 3.3 billion
U.S. dollars, of which around 1.6 billion for the UN regular
budget, 1.7 billion for peace-keeping missions and 4.9 million for
the International Tribunals for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The overdue amounts included 1.2 billion dollars that should
have been contributed by the United States before 1996, which was
followed by Russia, with more than 400 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. share of the UN regular budget should amount to 25
percent, down to 12 percent in effect last year. It should account
for 31 percent of the peacekeeping dues, but paid off only 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
Judging from its current budgetary problems, Washington appears
not intended to pay the debt it owed to U.N.
</P>
<P>
UN press official in Geneva said that it still remains unknown
if the U.N. budget goals for the year 1996-1997 will be fulfilled.
The budget, approved at the U.N. General Assembly last December,
is the first ever aiming at achieving "zero nominal growth" with
real cost reductions of over 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1996 assessments, some 1.1 billion dollars will be
assessed for the regular budget, with some 275.3 million assessed
this week for eight peace-keeping operations, including
assessments for mandate periods in 1995.
</P>
<P>
By January 23, 12 member states had paid up their 1996 regular
budget dues and 13 others had made a partial payment. U.N. had
received some 93.6 million dollars for the regular budget, 42.5
million for peacekeeping missions and more than 297,000 dollars
for the International Tribunals.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Petrovsky, Director-General of the United Nations
Office at Geneva, said Monday, "Nevertheless, we are faced with
the stark realities of dwindling resources. As a result, we are
unfortunately left with no choice but to take immediate action,
which will include cutting some facilities and services in Geneva
for all our partners."
</P>
<P>
In UN Geneva office, some 250 staff are expected to be reduced
in the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
