<HEADLINE> Mugabe, Muzorewa, Sithole To Run For Zimbabwean Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean current President
Robert Mugabe and two opposition leaders will contend for the
next presidency of Zimbabwe in the race scheduled for March 16 and
17, this year.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition candidates are leader of the opposition
ZANU (Ndonga) Reverend Ndabaningi Sithole and Bishop Abel
Muzorewa of the united parties.
</P>
<P>
The three candidates qualified for the presidential poll at
the close of the nomination court in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
Two other relatively unknown opposition presidential
aspirants, businessman and politician Egypt Dzinemunenzva and
Harare economist Clive Samvura limped off before the race began.
</P>
<P>
Presiding officer, Registrar-General Tobaiwa Mudede said
Dzinemunenzva and Samvura had failed to score the required number
of a minimum of 10 nominators from each of the country's 10
political provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party, the Forum Party of Zimbabwe, the Front
for Popular Democracy and the Front for Democratic Reform are
boycotting the elections citing flaws in the constitution and
electoral act which they say favor the ruling ZANU (PF). 
</P>
</TEXT>
