<HEADLINE> US Begins to Withdraw Diplomats From Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
began to evacuate all its diplomats and government personnel from
Sudan because they are vulnerable to terrorist attack in the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
About 30 U.S. Embassy staff members and their families will
leave Sudan by commercial airlines over the next few days, State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns announced here last night.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 2,100 U.S. citizens who live in Sudan are
being urged to leave that country.
</P>
<P>
"We regret this decision, but it was necessary for the safety
of United States citizens," Burns said, adding that the United
States has repeatedly sought assurance from the government of
Sudan that it would protect Americans but has not received them.
</P>
<P>
Burns noted that the withdrawal is not a break in diplomatic
relations and the United States will establish an office in the
region to maintain its liaison with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the United States and Sudan have been tense
since General Omar al-Bashir seized power in a 1989 coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department has put Sudan on its list of those
states which are accused of sponsoring international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The United States made the decision to withdraw all its
diplomats from Sudan out of security fears triggered by a U.N.
Security Council demand yesterday that Sudan surrender three men
suspected of trying to assassinate Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
