<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Plans to Make Insider Trading Civil Wrong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Steps to make insider dealing a
civil wrong rather than a criminal offense are under active
consideration by the Securities and Investments Board (SIB), the
chief City regulator in London.
</P>
<P>
The move, which could trigger a sharp increase in the rate of
successful legal actions, is detailed in the SIB's management plan
for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Barely 200 cases have been referred to the prosecuting
authorities by the Stock Exchange since 1980, when insider dealing
became an offense in Britain. Cases take up to four years to reach
the courts, and convictions are rare.
</P>
<P>
Civil remedies would ease successful legal actions by sharply
reducing the burden of proof. Under the present system, a
prosecutor needs to prove beyond all reasonable doubt that an
offense has been committed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
