<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cote D'Ivoire Offers Venue Of Possible S.Leonean Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Cote d'Ivoire has offered
Yamassoukro as a venue for any peace talks between the Sierra
Leonean military government and the rebel RUF, Sierra Leonean
Head of State Brigadier Julius Maada Bio said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bio said, "there has not been any contact" with the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) so far but disclosed he was
informed by the International Committee of the Red Cross on
Thursday that RUF leader Corporal Foday Sankoh had indicated that
"he would like to talk to Bio directly".
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean new leader was addressing his first press
conference since he came to power in a January 16 coup and made
an offer of dialogue to the RUF the following day.
</P>
<P>
He gave no further details but re-emphasized that he would
"pursue peace at any price for Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
Diplomats are of the view that Cote d'Ivoire is one of the
countries "crucial to the peace process" in Sierra Leone as it
has repeatedly been accused of siding with the RUF, a claim which
it denies.
</P>
<P>
Later last month, the RUF indicated that it was prepared to
hold talks with the government, their first unconditional offer
of negotiations since the beginning of the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Reporting on his rounds of visits to sub-regional countries in
recent days, Bio said for Sierra Leone "to achieve a sustainable
peace, it needs the support of Ghana, Guinea and Nigeria".
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria had also "offered to host any mediation
efforts" to bring a halt to the five-year-old rebel war, which
had wrecked Sierra Leone's mining-based economy and driven more
than one-third of the country's four million people from their
home.
</P>
<P>
On the possible postponement of the planned February 26
elections, Bio said that the date had been set by a consultative
delegates conference last August and that "if there should be any
change, it will be up to that meeting to decide the issue".
</P>
<P>
The RUF has said it wanted the elections to be postponed "so
that we can have time to restore peace in the country".
</P>
<P>
The elections had been pledged to end the civil war by Former
Head of State Valentine Strasser, who was ousted by Bio in the
January 16 coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
