<HEADLINE> Major Tax Policy Adopted In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
adopted a major tax policy to want parastatals and commercialized
state-owned companies to pay corporate tax and remit half of
their net earnings to treasury.
</P>
<P>
It was announced today by Senior Secretary for Finance Chakles
Kuwaza. He said that his ministry had been directed by the
cabinet to devise a dividend policy, as well amend the income tax
act to remove corporate tax exemptions for all public
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said today that the government could earn as much as
22 million US dollars from dividends from those state enterprises
making profits, although the figure could be substantially higher
when corporate tax was included.
</P>
<P>
President of Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce Danny Meyer
immediately welcomed the government move, but said that the
government should speed-up its privatization program because
''the government is there to govern and not run businesses''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
