<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Rise 2.5 Percent Last Year in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices rose only
2.5 percent in U.S. last year, the smallest increase since a 1.1
percent rise in 1986, according to a report by the U.S. Labour
Department today.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the prices increase was below 3
percent in the past four years running.
</P>
<P>
Both in 1994 and 93, consumer prices increased 2.7 percent
respectively, and 2.9 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The labour Department also said that consumer prices were up a
modest 0.2 percent in December with moderation in most categories
helping to offset a big increase of energy prices.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the docile inflation report would give the
Federal Reserve more leeway to reduce interests rate in the future
to spur a flagging U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve, citing the low inflation pressure as a
main reason, cut the federal fund rate and discount rate both by a
quarter of a percentage point on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was immediately followed by the announcement of major banks
that they were cutting their prime lending rate, the benchmark for
consumer and business loan, from 8.5 percent to 8.25 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
