<HEADLINE> China, Hong Kong Continue Winning Streak in Asian Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China is one more step closer
to the top spot of Group Two as it scored another win at the Asian
Cup soccer qualifying tournament here this evening, beating the
Philippines 7-0.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese led 1-0 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
In the other second-round action this evening, hosts Hong Kong
beat Macao 4-1, after leading 1-0 at the break.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese national side won over an unfancied Macao team 7-1
in the tournament's opening round Tuesday although its performance
was far from being up to its usual caliber.
</P>
<P>
But the team displayed a much better teamwork this evening
which helped them run over their Filipino opponents.
</P>
<P>
With an 8-0 clean victory over the Philippines in the first
round, Hong Kong had been expected by local fans to score another
big-margin win, this time over its neighbors Macao.
</P>
<P>
But the Hong Kong team was probably steamed up too late, in the
later stage of the second half, when it scored three consecutive
goals within the span of five minutes.  Disappointed fans blamed
the team for their less active play at the game's early stage.
</P>
<P>
China and Hong Kong, with two straight wins after two rounds of
competition, are level with six points each on the team standing
table. But the Chinese scored 14 goals against one lost while
Hong Kong put in 12 goals also against one lost.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, the top favorites with superior personal skills
and experience for the three-day event, are generally expected to
be able to win over Hong Kong on the tournament's final day
Sunday. With the win, China will qualify for the Asian Cup finals
slated for December this year in the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Summit To Be Held In Mid-February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) announced today that a world food
summit will be held in Rome, Italy, from February 13 to 17.
</P>
<P>
In a statement simultaneously issued here, FAO
Director-General Jacques Diouf said the summit, expected to be
the biggest ever get-together of heads of state and government,
will seek commitment to a policy statement and a plan of action
to eradicate hunger the world over.
</P>
<P>
The world food production will have to increase by more than
75 percent over the next 30 years to keep pace with population
growth, Diouf said.
</P>
<P>
"We must prepare now to feed about nine billion people who
will inhabit the world by 2030 from 5.8 billion people today," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the summit will marshal at the highest political level
a global consensus and commitment needed to implement policies,
programs and strategies that will lead to the virtual eradication
of hunger in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to FAO, some 800 million people are chronically
undernourished in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Every day, one out of five people in the developing countries
cannot get enough food to meet their daily needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
