<HEADLINE> US Initiative on Cyprus Issue Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. initiative aimed to
break the deadlock in the stalled Cyprus peace process will be
postponed, U.S. ambassador to Cyprus Richard Boucher indicated
here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. has not relinquished its commitment to
promote its initiative for a Cyprus settlement in 1996, the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Boucher outlined the position during a meeting with Cyprus
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides, who has asked to be formally
informed about the U.S. intention after the Aegean crisis broke
out between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Richard Holbrooke announced
Wednesday that in view of this week's Greek-Turkish crisis, he
will embark on a trouble-shooting mission to the region in
February to defuse the tension in the Aegean Sea, instead of
launching the previously planned initiative on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Yiannakis Cassoulides said the American initiative, originally
planned to be launched in 1996, will not start with Holbrooke's
forthcoming visit to Cyprus, scheduled to take place in
mid-February, when Holbrooke visits Athens and Ankara to bridge
differences between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said this development does not mean the Cyprus issue
and efforts to settle it will not be raised during Holbrooke's
visit to the three countries.
</P>
<P>
"But we are not going to see repeated and pain-staking
efforts in shuttle diplomacy in the three capitals, a move
initially planned," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides said Holbrooke is "welcomed in Cyprus irrespective
of his contribution" and said the American initiative is
postponed until after Holbrooke's departure from the diplomatic
service. Holbrooke, who brokered the Bosnian peace accord, was
said to be leaving the government by the end of February.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that the key to a solution to the
Cyprus problem is in Ankara, noting that a steady government
in Turkey was needed to deal with the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
