<HEADLINE> Macao Papers Praise Premier Li's Speech on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Macao newspapers have published a
 series of commentaries, praising Chinese Premier Li Peng's speech
</P>
<P>
on Taiwan as a blow to separatism in Taiwan and as an emphasis
on "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Macao Daily News said in a commentary that Premier Li's speech
pointed out the fundamental difference between the Chinese people
and the Taiwan authorities lies in the fact that the Chinese
people insist on "one China" while the Taiwan authorities want to
split Taiwan from China.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that the Taiwan authorities are playing a
double game. On the one hand, they intend to grab some
"international space" by making "two Chinas"; on the other hand,
they claim that they want to improve relations across the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
<P>
It noted that all these activities can not cover the true
intention of splitting China.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li's speech has seen through these tactics and stressed
 that relations across the Taiwan Straits can not be improved
unless the Taiwan authorities give up making "two Chinas" or "one
China, one Taiwan" in deed rather than in word.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the struggle against the splitting of China and
the "independence of Taiwan" will never end as long as the Taiwan
authorities are doing something to split the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that Li's speech was a major blow to the
Taiwan authorities as it pointed out that, in whatever ways the
leadership of Taiwan is chosen, the fact that the leaders in
Taiwan will be leaders of a locality in China and that Taiwan is
part of China will never change.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese-language newspaper Correio
Sino-Macaense said that Li's speech has stressed "the urgency of
solving the problem of Taiwan" after China resumes exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Li's speech has revealed that the prerequisite
and basis of the reunification of China is the principle of "one
China" policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
