<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Enjoys Trade Surplus in First Half of 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's (EU)
trade surplus with the rest of the world reached 8.4 billion ECUs
(about 11 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of 1995,
EUROSTAT said today.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was 2.6 billion ECUs in the first quarter and 5.8
billion ECUs in the second quarter of last year, according to
figures released by EUROSTAT, the EU's statistical office based in
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose by 5.8 percent and exports by 10.3 percent
during the period.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by the EU's three new member-states, Austria, Sweden
and Finland, growth in intra-EU trade was higher in the first half
of last year than in the same period in 1994, accounting for
nearly two-thirds of total trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
