<HEADLINE> Former Hamas Leader Elected to Palestinian Legislative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Imad Falouji, Former leader
of the Islamic resistance Movement or Hamas, has been elected to
the 88-strong Palestinian legislative council in fresh ballot in
the North Gaza District, according to a report of JMCC, a
Palestinian press service based in east Jerusalem today.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Sharafi, an activist of the Popular Front for
Liberation of Palestine (PFLP) running as an independent
candidate, was also elected in the revote, which took place
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad Akasheh and Khader Abu El-Nada, both independent
candidates, were dropped from the provisional winning list.
</P>
<P>
CEC official Riad Khodari explained that the revote at two
polling stations in the Jabalya refugee camp was conducted
because the Central Election Commission (CEC) found evidence of
cheating during the January 20 general elections. The new
vote at polling station No. 76 was ordered as no observers
were present during the original vote count, while at station
No. 39, a scuffle between supporters of rival candidates had
obstructed the process.
</P>
<P>
During the revote Wednesday, some 300 policemen guarded the
two schools where the polling stations were located. Most of
the 2,320 registered voters were reported to have cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
Complaints about irregularities and rigging in several voting
districts have held up announcement of the final election
results. Khodrai said that final results would only be
announced after vote counts have been reviewed in all 16 election
districts and all complaints have been investigated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
