<HEADLINE> Tensions Between Muslims, Croats High in Bosnian City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Tensions between Muslims and
Croats in the Bosnian city of Kul en Vakuf intensified as the
Bosnian Croat army occupied the area, Muslim-controlled Sarajevo
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Bosnian Croat soldiers had robbed and burned
down 1,000 Muslim houses, forcing 6,000 Muslim residents to flee
the city.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dayton peace accord signed in Paris last
December, all foreign forces, including Croatian troops, had to
leave the area by January 24. But Bosnian Croat forces took over
the city immediately after the Croatian troops pulled out.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Muslim-Croat federation is waiting for
arbitration by Hans Koschnik, the European Union's representative
stationed in Bosnia, on how to divide the city of Mostar. 
