<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Soccer Player Faces Ban for Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Former Arsenal club's player
Roger Stanislaus will confront the Football Association (FA) later
on Thursday and could face an unprecedented two or three-year ban
for drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old tested positive for cocaine after a game last
November.
</P>
<P>
Stanislaus is expected to defend the misconduct charge by
insisting that it was used socially, with no intention of boosting
his performance.
</P>
<P>
The traces showed up after he was selected for random testing
following Leyton Orient's game at Barnet in the division three
match on November 25.
</P>
<P>
He has been suspended by his club since the test result was
announced last month.
</P>
<P>
The FA will call medical advisors to insist that the strength
of the positive test suggests he could have taken it as late as
the morning of the Saturday game.
</P>
<P>
They will also present the hearing with evidence which proves
that cocaine can act as a performance-enhancer.
</P>
<P>
Tranmere club's trainee Jamie Hughes, the first to be charged
with using a performance-enhancer, was caught in a training ground
test.
</P>
<P>
Though he claimed someone else had put the drug in his drink in
a nightclub, he was banned from competition for two years in last
July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
