<HEADLINE> Southwestern Supply Route to Kabul Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The highway linking the
Afghan capital of Kabul with the country's southern and
southwestern provinces has been reopened to traffic, bringing some
relief to the Kabul residents, a report from Kabul said today.
</P>
<P>
Land mines and unexploded shells on the supply route were
cleared last week, the report quoted military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 buses and trucks loaded with wheat flour, cooking
oil, firewood, sugar, rice and charcoal have entered the city
through the route since its reopening.
</P>
<P>
The highway was closed in October last year due to fighting
between the Taliban Islamic student militia and the forces of
President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the International Committee for Red Cross (ICRC) is
planning to airlift relief supplies to Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Flights to Kabul would start Saturday and at least three cargo
planes would carry relief supplies from Peshawar every day,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Red Crescent said that one thousand tons of
flour and ghee would be supplied to Kabul this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
