<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Nepali Cities Classified as Submetropolises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government today
classified three cities as submetropolitan municipalities in
accordance with the Municipality Act.
</P>
<P>
The three cities, Lalitpur in the Kathmandu Valley, Pokhara of
Western Nepal and Biratnagar of Southern Nepal, would achieve
greater success in meeting the challenges of urban development and
providing services, the Local Development Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1992 Municipality Act, Nepali cities with a
population of at least 100,000, an annual income of 20 million
rupees (about 40,000 US dollars) and urban facilities like
electricity, roads, drinking water and communications, can be
classified as submetropolis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government has declared Kathmandu, capital of the
country, a metropolitan city.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government's move to classify metropolitan and
submetropolitan cities is believed to be part of its
decentralization policy to give more authority to local
governments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
