<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila to Open More Avenues for Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
pressing legislators to approve three key changes in the foreign
investments act (FIA) in a bid to attract more foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Rizalino Navarro said today that
the proposed measures, endorsed in a bill filed by Senator Gloria
Arroyo, are aiming to open up more avenues for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
First, the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) proposed to
lower the paid-in capital requirement for foreign-owned domestic
enterprises from 500,000 US dollars to 150,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The present requirement of half a million dollars has served as
a deterrent to the entry of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Small enterprises would still be amply protected despite the
reduced minimum equity requirement, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Second, the DTI suggested the scrapping of the three-year
requirement before a domestic enterprise can change its status to
an export enterprise.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the moment a domestic market enterprise
exports at least 60 percent of its yearly output, it should be
considered an export enterprise," Navarro explained.
</P>
<P>
Third, in line with the government's deregulation policy, the
DTI recommended that FIA's negative list C be deleted permanently.
</P>
<P>
The list prohibits any foreign investments in the ownership and
operation of cockpits and limits foreign equity to 40 percent in
some service sectors.
</P>
<P>
Among them are travel agencies, tourist lodging services,
pension houses and tourist inns, convention and conference
organizers and life and non-life insurance agencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Senator Ramon Magsaysay Jr., chairman of the Senate
Committee on Economic Affairs, said that legislators favor the
changes proposed by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we hope to follow DTI's proposals and decide which
areas to open up and shut up."
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "as much as possible, we do not want to hurt
small- and medium-sized enterprises."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
