<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Intends to Host World Cup Cricket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan cricket officials
said here on Thursday that Sri Lanka still intended to host four
World Cup matches despite a bomb blast in the capital which killed
72 people and injured more than 1,400.
</P>
<P>
Thilanga Sumathipala, vice president of the Sri Lankan Cricket
Board, said there were no plans to drop out as one of the three
hosts of the tournament with the first match just two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
Australia is considering asking for a change of venue or
forfeiting their World Cup cricket match in Sri Lanka following
Wednesday's bomb attack, which occurred close to the hotel where
the Australian team is to stay.
</P>
<P>
Sumathipala said the cricket board "will review the situation
with the Australian High Commission here and with our minister of
sports but the matches will go ahead as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"All five teams including Sri Lanka are important to us and we
would not risk our players if there was an element of danger to
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, co-hosts of the World Cup with India and Pakistan,
are scheduled to play three of their four matches in
Colombo: against Australia on February 17, Zimbabwe on February 21
and the West Indies on February 25.
</P>
<P>
The fourth match is against Kenya on March 6 in the hill resort
of Kandy in central Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
