<HEADLINE> German Firms to Invest in Philippine Shipbuilding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Two German firms are planning to
build a shipyard on Mindanao Island in partnership with a local
firm.
</P>
<P>
Jurgen Rudolph, project manager of the Hamburg-based Komrowski
Maritim GMBH, said today that the company, together with
shipbuilding firm Blohm and Voss AEG, will establish a
shipbuilding and repair facility in Davao city.
</P>
<P>
Pending the completion of the negotiation on project financing,
Rudolph did not reveal the name of the local partner.
</P>
<P>
The project, estimated to cost between 50 and 70 million US
dollars, may avail of some long-term financing from DEG (Deutsche
Investitionsund Entwicklungsgesellschaft MBH), Germany's state-run
investment company.
</P>
<P>
Komrowski is one of the 15 companies represented in the
business mission from the city of Hamburg led by Ernard
Rittershaus, state-minister of economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The mission is here to seek business opportunities in the
Philippines. 
</P>
