<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Monitor Possible Three Gorges Environmental Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China plans to establish an
ecology and environment monitoring network to keep an eye on the
changes that might be brought about by the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
The government has approved the allocation of 90 million yuan
(about 11 million US dollars) for the setting up of the network,
Xinhua learned from a conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project, the world's largest water-control
endeavor, is expected to effectively control floods on the Yangtze
River, provide a huge supply of electricity, improve navigation
conditions on the Yangtze and bring about other benefits.
</P>
<P>
It will also, however, change the river's hydrology, bring
about environmental and ecological changes to the project's
reservoir area, and to the river's middle and lower reaches and
its estuary.
</P>
<P>
So the government feels it is imperative to establish a
network, including several centers and laboratories, to monitor
the changes that might take place in the process of the
construction of the gigantic project.
</P>
<P>
The project will take 17 years to complete, and is expected to
submerge 600 sq km of land, affecting 21 counties and 840,000
people. By the year 2008 more than one million people will have
been resettled.
</P>
<P>
The network will be established with the joint efforts of the
Three Gorges Project Construction Committee of the State Council,
State Bureau of Environmental Protection, China Academy of
Sciences, ministries of water conservancy, forestry and public
health, State Meteorological Administration, and the China Yangtze
River Project Development Corporation, as well as Hubei and
Sichuan provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
