<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,150 Vietnamese Boat People in Malaysia To Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 1 (Xinhua) -- About 1,150 Vietnamese
boat people, including 84 people identified as rabble-rousers of
last month's riot at Sungai Besi Transit Camp in Kuala Lumpur,
have volunteered for repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The camp's commandant Lim Boon Boo told the press here today
that these troublemakers had had enough of fighting against
repatriation and had given up hope of being resettled in third
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the commandant, some boat people were already fed
up with the troublemakers and asked the authorities to isolate
them.
</P>
<P>
An outbreak occurred on January 18 at the Sungai Besi Transit
Camp when some Vietnamese boat people threw stones at the police.
The incident saw seven policemen and 17 Vietnamese injured. One of
the Vietnamese died in Kuala Lumpur Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The rioters burned down two blocks of residential buildings and
eleven Vietnamese were arrested by the police.
</P>
<P>
"I was told by the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) representative here that more and more inmates
were coming forward to register for voluntary repatriation after
the riot," Lim said.
</P>
<P>
"After the rabble-rousers were segregated, I counseled them
until they realized that there is no point in persisting with
their actions," Lim told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The camp currently houses 4,410 Vietnamese boat people and 151
are expected to leave for home on February 6.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
