<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferguson 12-match Ban Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Everton striker Duncan Ferguson
won his legal battle on Thursday to overturn a 12-match ban.
</P>
<P>
Scottish judge Lord Macfadyean ruled that the Scottish
Football Association's (SFA) disciplinary committee had acted
beyond their powers in imposing the ban.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson was suspended for 12 matches by the SFA for a
head-butting incident involving Raith defender John McStay in
April 1994 when he was playing for Rangers. He was also sentenced
to three months in prison for assault and spent 44 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
His lawyers had claimed that the SFA disciplinary committee
acted beyond its powers by imposing the ban for an offence which
was only acted on after a report by the match supervisor.
</P>
<P>
Lord Macfadyean confirmed in a written judgement that his
appeal to have the ban overturned at a judicial review at the
Edinburgh Court of Session on January 19 had been successful.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson, who has already missed five matches, will now be
available for Everton's premier league clash with Southampton on
Saturday and is free to play in this year's European
championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
