<HEADLINE> Syrian-Israeli Peace Talks End Without Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Syria announced here today
that the Syrian-Israeli peace talks ended Wednesday night in the
American state of Maryland achieved no substantial results despite
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's participation.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources here, Syria accused Israel of
having failed to do something to serve the peace process based on
the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They said that there are some Israeli currents seeking to
achieve regional ambitions and dreams of hegemony under the guise
of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Christopher's upcoming Middle East tour --
which is to start next Tuesday -- would focus on security
arrangements including early-warning stations and demilitarized
zones.
</P>
<P>
There are speculations that Christopher will offer some ideas
and proposals to serve as compromises for the attitudes of the two
negotiating parties.
</P>
<P>
The sources expect no breakthrough, but they said Christopher's
Middle East tour may result in intensifying the forthcoming rounds
of Syrian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the two countries have been stalled for
more than four years, maily over the security arrangements in the
Golan Heights and peace terms after an eventual Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Christopher's planned five-day visit will be his 17th
negotiating trip to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
