<HEADLINE> Mandela On Economy In Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa was on
the verge of an economic breakthrough, South African President
Nelson Mandela said here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a Southern African Development Community (SADC)
consultative conference, Mandela said regional cooperation would
allow southern African governments to raise living standards.
</P>
<P>
"Southern Africa has most of the characteristics of a winning
region," said Mandela, adding that SADC needed to capitalize
on the mutually beneficial possibilities and harmonize strategies
on matters of common interest.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela pointed out that the SADC region, being
characterized by political stability, democracy and far-reaching
programs of reconstruction within a framework of financial
discipline, had become an ideal destination for investment.
</P>
<P>
Having realized the SADC region's potential as a viable
investment prospect, the World Economic Forum and the other
investment conferences during 1995 had provided potential
investors with the opportunity to acquaint themselves with the
regional investment environment and to set up a platform for
joint ventures with regional investors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a proposed SADC trade protocol, to be completed
soon, will simplify trade relations within the community and
present the region as one entity to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Mandela stressed that the SADC region would
benefit by earning more foreign exchange, creating sustainable
jobs through intra-regional and inter-regional trade, improving
credit worthiness and increasing economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
Growth and development were indeed better tackled in a
collective manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also reaffirmed that South Africa was fully committed
to working as a full and equal partner towards the realization of
a better region for all, saying South Africa's success was linked
to that of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
