<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Chun's Request for Delayed Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Seoul District Court today
rejected former South Korean President Chun Doo-hwan's request to
have his graft trial postponed, saying that it will start on
February 5 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Chun, who is currently receiving medical treatment at the
National Police Hospital here, submitted a reqeust to the court
for a delay in the trial through his lawyer Suk Jin-kang on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that he could hardly attend the trial session because
he was suffering from nausea and dizziness, apparent side effects
from his three-week-long fast in prison.
</P>
<P>
"If and when Chun's health deteriorates during his trial, we'll
then judge whether or not to put it off," a Seoul District Court
judge said.
</P>
<P>
Chun has been indicted for raising a huge slush fund during his
1980-1988 presidency, including 270 million U.S. dollars worth of
bribes received from businessmen in return for granting them
contracts on state projects.
</P>
<P>
He has also been indicted for insurrection and treason along
with former President Roh Tae-woo for their roles in the 1979
military mutiny and the 1980 military suppression of the
pro-democracy movement in Kwangju.
</P>
<P>
Chun, who loomed large as the Army strong man after the 1979
military mutiny, seized power on August 27, 1980 and ruled the
nation until February 1988, when he was succeeded by Roh Tae-woo.
</P>
</TEXT>
