<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Lowers Benchmark Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) today lowered its benchmark rates by 25 basis
points, following the US decision to cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
HKMA reduced the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF) rates by
0.25 percent, at which short-time borrowing and lending are
conducted between commercial banks and the authority, which acts
as a central bank.
</P>
<P>
The LAF bid rate shed to 4 percent from 4.25, and the offer
rate from 6.25 to 6 percent, both with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
Sources from HKMA said that the cut is in line with the 25
basis point decrease in the US discount rate, announced by the
Federal Open Market Committee at four o'clock (Hong Kong time)
this morning.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the action taken by HKMA, it is up to the
individual banks to decide the primary lending rate and interest
rates on deposits with maturities of seven days and beyond. The
Hong Kong Association of Banks will call the shots in setting
interest rates on retail deposits that mature in less than seven
days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
