<HEADLINE> Downhill Racers Return to Garmisch Piste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Kandahar piste in Germany's
Garmisch-Partenkirchen will stage two World Cup downhills and a
super giant slalom this weekend, the first time since Austria's
Ulrike Maier was killed there two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup racers will compete in the two events before the
best among them leave for Spain and the world championships in
Sierra Nevada from February 11 through to 25.
</P>
<P>
With International Skiing Federation (FIS) officials still
facing a possible trial on charges of negligent killing over
Maier's death, Garmisch organisers have focused their attention
on increasing safety this year.
</P>
<P>
They failed to hold a downhill last year because they did not
have enough money to make sure that the piste was secure.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that they have spent 250,000 marks (167,785
U.S. dollars) improving safety nets and barriers at the side of
the run and in the finish area.
</P>
<P>
Maier crashed at one of the less challenging stretches when she
lost control of one her skis.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 several racers were also injured and forced to miss
the Albertville Olympics after losing control and crashing on an
icy run there.
</P>
<P>
Garmisch spokesman Rudi Maerkl said on Thursday that they had
used the most up-to-date technology for safety. But he added that
something unexpected might happen and could not be avoided due to
"human elements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
