<HEADLINE> Accord With IMF Vital, British Minister Tells Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain will resume balance
of payments support to Tanzania after the country reaches an agreement
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
This pre-condition was stated here on Wednesday by Ms. Baroness
Lynda Chalker, British Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth
Affairs responsible for Overseas Development, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"I have said that we will release half of our outstanding 8.5
million Sterling Pounds when the government (of Tanzania) reaches
agreement with the IMF on the shadow program," she said.
</P>
<P>
Upon receiving such an assurance, Britain will consider releasing
the second 4.25 million Sterling Pounds, even before the end of the
current financial year.
</P>
<P>
"That leaves an outstanding pledge of 15 millionn Sterling Pounds.
A formal agreement with IMF and the World Bank will be a
pre-condition for the release of this further pledge," she noted.
</P>
<P>
The British minister observed that the government still had a
hard road ahead on the economy, but it was important for it to get
the economy under control.
</P>
<P>
She repeated her initial statement that she had been
encouraged by the statements from the new Tanzanian
administration and its early actions such as the mini-budget.
</P>
<P>
"I had useful discussions with the minister of agriculture and
health which will remain key areas for British suport,"she said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed, "We wish to assure you that, provided the government
demonstrates commitment to the reform program, the United Kingdom,
as a close friend, will give you moral encouragement, technical
co-operation and financial support."
</P>
<P>
The British minister left here later Wednesday for Swaziland
before going to South Africa for an official visit.  enditem

