<HEADLINE> Boeing 777s Reshape HK Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's leading airline
Cathay Pacific had its first Boeing 777-200 landing in the
territory today, which is part of its fleet replacement program
under way.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 777, the world's largest twin-engine aircraft, will
take part in a 90-cycle test on its engine operations around Asia
and Australia before the scheduled delivery in May.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific ordered 11 Boeing 777s in 1992, which are
currently valued at some 2.6 billion US dollars. The first four
will be delivered in May and the rest in a improved version, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The new types are designed to have 343 seats and large cargo
capacity, with less fuel consumption and lower maintenance
cost. The first four Boeing 777-200 will fly on the routes between
Hong Kong and cities in the Asian-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific has planned to replace its old models with the
latest airliners by the year of 2000. It has placed firm orders
for 19 Boeing and Airbus Industrie aircraft, as well as less than
40 options for further purchase.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 12 Airbus Industrie planes have been put into use
since the first one delivered in August, 1994.  
</P>
