<HEADLINE> Australia's Trade With Vietnam Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia has expanded its
trade relations with Vietnam since Australian trade minister
visited that country last year.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Trade Bob McMullan said in a news release today
that Australia had confirmed 150 million Australian dollar (112.5
million US dollar) worth of business with Vietnam since he led a
trade delegation to Hanoi in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said that Australian companies are negotiating another 170
million Australian dollar (127.5 million US dollar) worth of
business with the Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
He led a mission of 18 Australian companies to the fourth
meeting of the Australia-Vietnam Joint Trade and Economic
Cooperation Committee (JTECC) held in Hanoi last September.
</P>
<P>
These companies represented a variety of sectors of the
Australian industry, including energy, mining, communications and
information technology, construction and building products and
food processing.
</P>
<P>
Most of the mission members secured business ranging between
one million to 30 million Australian dollars (0.75 million to 22.5
million US dollars) during the visit.
</P>
<P>
"The deals that were done on the spot in Vietnam show the level
of enthusiasm there for Australian products and services,"
McMullan said.
</P>
<P>
"We set out to strengthen trade relations between Australia and
Vietnam and try to remove any barriers to bilateral trade and
investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mission members also followed up the visit by using the
government-run Austrade offices in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City to
gain more business.
</P>
<P>
The mission also helped Australian companies identify possible
expansion into the Vietnamese domestic sector and services sector,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Australian-Vietnamese trade totaled 450 million Australian
dollars (337.5 million US dollars) last year. Australia is now the
seventh largest overseas investor in Vietnam, with a total value
of approved projects in Vietnam standing at one billion Australian
dollars (745 million US dollars).  
</P>
