<HEADLINE> hke020146--Indonesia to Allow Private Refineries to Sell Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
soon allow private oil refineries to distribute and sell their
products on the domestic market but will continue to control the
fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
The government is now making assessment on a new bill to revise
law No. 8/1971 which grants the state-owned oil company Pertamina
a monopoly in processing, distribution and marketing oil on the
domestic market, according to sources from the Ministry of Mines
and Energy here today.
</P>
<P>
The government has licensed 12 private firms to operate
refineries with total investments of 21.1 billion US dollars in
the country. The owners of the 12 firms are still waiting for the
new bill before they decide whether to go ahead with their
projects.
</P>
<P>
The government will still be able to control the fuel prices
because the state-run oil company Pertamina will remain the market
leader.
</P>
<P>
Pertamina, which has nine refineries with a combined processing
capacity of 895,000 barrels per day, will be able to act as price
setter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
