<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corruption Causes Huge Losses in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government audit
agency disclosed that it has to deal with thousands of cases
involving more than 2 trillion rupiah (873.36 million US dollars)
in corruption-related losses at government offices and state-owned
firms.
</P>
<P>
Soedarjono, head of the agency, said in a recent hearing before
the Budgetary Commission of the House of Representatives that the
figure reflected losses incurred up until last September,
according to a report of "Economic Bulletin" here today.
</P>
<P>
Citing an example, Soedarjono said in just the second quarter
(July-September) of the current fiscal year (1995-1996), his
office found 6,549 instances of financial irregularities and
corruption at government institutions and state firms, causing
losses of 186.29 billion rupiah (80.9 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the cases detected, 5,729 involving losses of 161.67 billion
rupiah (70.29 million us dollars) have not been followed up, he
said.
</P>
<P>
House members originally discovered the information upon their
visit to the agency's Jakarta branch.
</P>
<P>
Soedarjono explained that there is currently no system in place
to check up on the activities of government offices and if they
are being handled cost-efficiently.
</P>
<P>
He called on every ministry to improve its supervision
mechanisms in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
