<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Reopen Embassy in Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is not considering
reopening its embassy in Kabul even after the Afghan government
apologizes for the attack on the embassy, said a Pakistani Foreign
Office spokesman here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly briefing, the spokesman said the security
situation, the damaged embassy building and some other reasons
prevented Pakistan from reopening its embassy in the Afghan
capital.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the Afghan government had contacted the
Pakistani government, expressing "deep regret" and willingness to
pay 15.3 million US dollars for compensation.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan demanded the Afghan government to apologize and fully
compensate for the attack on its embassy on September 6 last year
when one embassy employee was killed and all diplomats, including
the ambassador, were injured.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has set these demands as conditions for reopening its
embassy in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said the apology and compensation and
the reopening of the embassy needed examining separately.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan never broke its diplomatic ties with
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Yet the physical condition in the Afghan capital was not
suitable for Pakistan to reopen its embassy there, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kabul has been besieged by the Taliban student militia since
last October.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, in a bid to topple the government of President
Burhanuddin Rabbani, has kept bombing the capital, which is
gripped by severe cold and food shortage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
