<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Carry Out Peat Land Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
been urged to ensure that its plan to convert one million hectares
of peat land into rice fields in central Kalimantan would be a
success.
</P>
<P>
Bambang Setiadi, chairman of Indonesian Peat Society,
acknowledged that by opening up the peat land, Indonesia could
reduce its imports of several important commodities, such as
soybeans, corn, peanuts and rice, according to a report by the
society received here today.
</P>
<P>
The import expense for these commodities, which total some 4
trillion rupiah (1.74 billion US dollars) per annum, can actually
be used to cultivate those crops on peat land, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to carry out the giant project as one of
its efforts to maintain the country's self-sufficiency in rice.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia used to be the biggest rice importer in the world but
became self-sufficient in 1984. Rice exports exceeded imports
until 1993, but the country had to start importing rice again in
1994 due to bad weather which caused drop in rice production.
</P>
<P>
The society said that a special authority for the project is
needed, considering the size of the project.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the importance of improving land fertility
after it is exposed.
</P>
<P>
It pointed that the project needs sound and careful management.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
