<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Cautioned not to Go Farther in Splitting Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China is in firm opposition to
the activities conducted by Taiwan authorities internationally to
create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" under the pretext
of making stopovers.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Chen Jian made this remark
at a routine press conference here today when asked to comment on
the US government's decision to allow Taiwan "Vice-President" Li
Yuan-zu to make another brief stopover in the country within one
month.
</P>
<P>
"We'd like to caution Taiwan authorities not to go farther down
on the road of splitting the motherland," Chen noted, "and we made
solemn representations with the US government."
</P>
<P>
China demanded the US government to honor its serious
commitments made in the three joint communiques between the two
countries and to strictly keep its relations with Taiwan within a
non-official scope, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the US not to create conditions for the Taiwan
authorities to conduct such activities that are aimed to split the
country, so as not to bring new harms to the Sino-US relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
