<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on China's IPR Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Chinese
Foreign Ministry said here today that it is "groundless" to
criticize China for inadequacy in combating piracy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Chen Jian, made the statement at a weekly press
conference when he was asked to comment on the US threat of trade
sanctions against China for "inadequacy in combating piracy."
</P>
<P>
"To protect intellectual property rights is one of China's
basic state policies," Chen said. "Since the adoption of the
reform and opening-up program, China has made tremendous efforts
in legislation, jurisdiction and law-enforcement to protect
intellectual property rights and has instituted a legal system for
IPR protection, a system which is up to the world standards."
</P>
<P>
"China and the United States have also signed with each other
an agreement on the protection of IPR," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, he said, China has taken a series of steps to
intensify its law-enforcement, such as cracking down on piracy,
and the country has achieved marked results in checking upon and
regulating the audio-visual and publishing markets and in
investigating and handling, according to law, cases concerning
those IPR-violating factories and people.
</P>
<P>
"It is groundless to criticize China for inadequacy in
combating piracy," the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
"It should be pointed out that IPR violation is an
international phenomenon which exists in many countries, including
the US.," he said, adding that China, on its part, is willing to
exchange experience and enhance cooperation with other countries
including the United States in IPR protection.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "to frequently make sanctions threat will
harm not only the bilateral cooperation in IPR protection but also
the overall Sino-US economic and trade ties. We are opposed to
such a practice." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
