<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intellectual Property Rights Protection in China Effective (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The head of the patent department of the US's General Electric
has said that China's current legal system and intellectual
property rights mechanism is "complete and rigorous," and that he
would not worry about his company's exporting its technology to
China.
</P>
<P>
To increase its role on curbing intellectual property rights
crimes, the Supreme People's Court has plans to establish a
special courtroom that provides training for local courts and
supervision for them, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Seven provincial higher courts and 12 intermediate courts have
special courtrooms for such cases. China's Patent Office and other
departments are now preparing to set up intellectual property
rights colleges, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two judges said that "China still has a lot to do" to
protect intellectual property rights from infringement. Cases have
often been tampered with by departments and local governments, so
the independent trial mechanism should be improved, Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang suggested that greater efforts be made to adjust the role
of courts and administrative bodies to speed up the process and
mete out proper punishment for those found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Both men said they believe that along with improvements in the
country's democratic legal framework, will come an increase in
protection of intellectual property rights, which will in turn
contribute to the nation's reforms and opening up to the outside
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
