<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans Military Operation to Free Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- There is the possibility for
the Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI) to apply a limited military
operation, should the Free Papua Movement (OPM) kidnappers move
the hostages out of Mapndum Village hideout in Irian Jaya.
</P>
<P>
ABRI chief of general staff lt. gen. Suyono revealed this in
Irian Jaya Wednesday, saying that the military operation to be
used in efforts to release the remaining 13 hostages held by OPM
does not mean a combat operation, according to reports reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
The ABRI headquarters has fully authorized the military
regional command of Trikora which covers Irian Jaya and Maluku to
use territorial and intelligence operations to release the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
The OPM on January 8 abducted 26 people including seven
foreigners who were conducting research in the remote Irian Jaya
village of Mapnduma. Later, 13 hostages including one foreigner
were released.
</P>
<P>
The OPM demanded the authorities for a Jakarta-recognition of a
separate west Papua state in Irian Jaya. However, the Indonesian
government has flatly turned down the demand, saying that the
majority of Irianese have chosen the area to be part of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On the release of the hostages, the ABRI and OPM have resumed
contact through radio.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
