<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intellectual Property Rights Protection in China Effective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A Taiwanese businessman
expected to take advantage of China's audio-video market to make a
large profit and had a large number of copies of Polygram, Warner,
and 21 other companies' CDs made on the mainland without
authorization, and sold them in Hong Kong, Taiwan, and the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
To his surprise, a Shanghai court, which handled a suit filed
by the 23 companies, ordered him to pay 6.67 million HK dollars in
compensation, 1.2 million yuan in fines, and 46,000 yuan in court
costs.
</P>
<P>
The case was only one of nearly 400 piracy cases handled by
Chinese courts nationwide last year. The number of cases involving
intellectual property rights has seen an annual increase of over
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, China has set up a complete and effective judicial
apparatus to protect intellectual property rights," two senior
Chinese judges said here today, adding that the Chinese courts
have been "offering fair, effective protection of these rights,
both domestic and foreign."
</P>
<P>
Since the first law on intellectual property rights was passed
in 1983, "China has been quick to establish a high-level mechanism
to protect them," said Yang Jinqi and Jiang Zhipei with the
intellectual property rights office of the Supreme People's Court
in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"The mechanism is consistent with the code of practices
commonly accepted in the international community," Yang added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese laws point out that the judicial system is the
final and most authoritative protector of intellectual property
rights, he explained, meaning, if administrative measures are not
effective enough, the aggrieved party can resort to the courts for
a higher decision.
</P>
<P>
The scope, time limits, investigative procedures, proof, and
legal definition of intellectual property rights as described in
the Chinese laws are consistent with international laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
In areas that are still in dispute in different parts of the
world, such the definition of rightful owner and the public
sphere, as well as other items, China uses the one that suits the
conditions best or seeks a compromise, according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
To see that the laws and regulations are correctly interpreted
and thoroughly applied, China has devoted a great deal of effort
for several years in training its judges.
</P>
<P>
Most of the judges handling intellectual property rights cases
are specialists trained in several fields or in various areas,
such as science and technology, or foreign languages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
