<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 08:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ambassador: Peace Impossible without Full Golan Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Israel
Martin Indyk has indicated that it is impossible for Israel to
reach a peace agreement with Syria without a full withdrawal from
the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
"We don't take the responsibility on what the line of
withdrawal should be, but it is up to the parties to negotiate,"
Indyk told Israel Television Wednesday night. "We will do our best
to facilitate the negotiations. We will not take our position or
impose our position."
</P>
<P>
"I think it is our judgement that it will not be possible to
achieve peace with Syria without a full withdrawal, but what
exactly that full withdrawal mean is up to the two parties to
define," he added.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that a U.S. official made such a
public statement concerning a full Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, which Israel seized from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, a statement issued Wednesday night by the United
States, Israel and Syria said that this week's talks at Maryland
laid solid bases for next week's shuttle diplomacy between Israel
and Syria by U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the talks significantly advances
discussion on key issues in a future peace treaty, adding there
is also difference of substance.
</P>
<P>
Israeli chief negotiator Uri Savir said that he believes there
will be another round of negotiations in Maryland following
Christopher's shuttle visit.
</P>
<P>
Savir told Israel Radio that this week, the Israeli and Syrian
delegations focused on security issues, but also discussed
normalization of relations and economic issues. The gaps between
the two sides were narrowed, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the U.S. has announced that it will play a more
central role in helping resolve the disputed issue of water
between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Another senior Israeli negotiator, Israel's Ambassador in
Washington Itamar Rabinovich said Wednesday night that peace with
Syria this year is a realistic possibility. However, he said that
deep gap remains on security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicolas Burns said Wednesday
night that the U.S. will press its bid for an agreement between
Israel and Syria even if Israel calls for early elections.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Washington that it is in the interests of
the United States that the two sides reach a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
So regardless of whether there will be early elections in
Israel, there will be no reduction in the intensity of
Washington's involvement in the peace talks, said Burns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
