<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 08:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Number of Chinese Rock Paintings in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, February 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 rock paintings
have been found in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region
over the past two decades, the largest number in the country,
according to Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
The paintings are mainly found in Alxa, Mount Yinshan, Ulanqab,
and Chifeng.
</P>
<P>
The work of tribal artists of the Xiongnu, Eastern Hu, and
Khitan, the rock paintings depict farming, grazing, hunting,
fighting, dancing, sacrificial rites, and reproduction.
</P>
<P>
Most of the work is the result of petroglyphs, with only a
small number painted with reddish brown paint.
</P>
<P>
Paintings of animals can be traced back some 10,000 years, and
those of hunting scenes to some 6,000-4,000 years ago, and
grazing, some 4,000-3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that some of the work at Mount Yinshan bears
similarities of style to bronzeware of the ancient Xiongnu people,
with the former being more developed in modelling, such as in a
design of a tiger swallowing an ox, which is found on both.
</P>
<P>
What is more unusual is that human figures on Chifeng rock
paintings look similar to those found in Lianyungang city in east
China's Jiangsu Province which is more than 1,500 km to the
southeast of Chifeng.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that exchanges involving rock painting art,
between the northern and southern parts of China, started in the
late stone age, thousands of years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
