<HEADLINE> Australian Cricket Players Fear Security in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MELBOURNE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian cricket players
and officials questioned the feasibility of playing in Sri Lanka
in the World Cup this month after the shocking bomb blast in
Colombo, Australian newspapers reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian reported that three players, Shane Warne, Ian
Healy and Mark Waugh were worried about their safety during the
one-day tournament on February 17, for which they would arrive
beforehand on February 14.
</P>
<P>
Healy was also quoted by Sydney's Daily Telegraph as saying
that the blast had put "the Sri Lankan leg of the World Cup in
jeopardy, that's for sure".
</P>
<P>
A huge bomb blast destroyed the building of the Central Bank in
Colombo on Wednesday, killing at least 53 people and injuring some
1,400 others.
</P>
<P>
Denis Rogers, chairman of the Australian Cricket Board (ACB),
was quoted in the Sydney Morning Herald as saying the ACB would
wait for advice from Australia's foreign ministry before making
any decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
