<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number of Grad School Entrance Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 240,000 people have
applied to take this year's graduate school entrance exams, the
highest number since China re-opened its grad schools in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide exam is scheduled for February 3 to 5. Some 30
percent more people are expected to take the exam this year than
last.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission said here today that 418
colleges and universities, 319 research institutes, the Party
School of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) and some local party schools and military colleges will
enroll a total of 46,000 people in master degree programs this
year.
</P>
<P>
The sources there said that south China's Hainan Province had
the greatest increase in the number of people, 65 percent more
than in 1995. Guangdong also saw a sharp increase in number of
applications, nearly 60 percent more this year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing and Shanghai had 57 and 37 percent more respectively,
applying this year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 120,000 working people applied, accounting for 58.4
percent of the total, and 31,000 more than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The commission says that because the government began to push
prosperity through scientific and educational development last
May, society has raised requirement for professional people.
</P>
<P>
Those working hope to increase their knowledge, and many large
and mid-sized enterprise restructuring projects need more
upper-level people than before.
</P>
<P>
College teachers showed a great deal of interest in the exam,
with nearly 16,000 of them applying, 37 percent more than last
year. The commission explain that younger teachers were encouraged
by the government's decision to strengthen training of teachers
and requiring teachers to have a better background.
</P>
<P>
The Qualification Rules for Teachers, issued by the State
Council at the end of 1995, asked all teachers to take a
nationwide qualifying and licensing exam.
</P>
<P>
According to the Teachers' Law, teachers must have a graduate
school education or higher if they teach in universities. Eight
percent of some 40,000 college teachers in China do not meet these
qualifications for formal schooling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
