<HEADLINE> Kenya Gets Credits From World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has decided to
provide Kenya with credits totaling 165 million U.S. dollars for
its infrastructure development, Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Of the credits, approved by the Board of Directors of the
World Bank on Tuesday, 115 million will be used for the
rehabilitation of the urban road network, and the remaining for
the Nairobi-Mombasa Road.
</P>
<P>
Both credits are from the International Development
Association (IDA), the bank's concessionary lending arm, and
are extended on standard IDA terms for a period of 40 years,
including 10 years of grace. 
</P>
