<HEADLINE> Shanghai Urbanites Decorating Their Bathrooms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Qing and her husband just
moved into a newly-refurbished two-room apartment last month,
after having paid nearly 30,000 yuan (about 3,164 US dollars) for
the decorating.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, who is a 28-year-old editor with a publishing house in
Shanghai, had the 3-sq-m bathroom refurbished using an American
Standard toilet, a Chinese Shenhua gas water heater, and pink tile
on the floor and walls, and notes, "It cost me more than 6,000
yuan for these things."
</P>
<P>
However, Zhou is just one of thousands of urbanites in Shanghai
who have spent their hard-earned savings on decorations for their
apartments, especially the bathroom, in response to the improved
standard of living.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over the past three years some 380,000
local families have moved into new apartments with a total floor
space of over 20 million sq m.
</P>
<P>
The refurbishing of these apartments cost on average 20,000
yuan last year, three times a workers' average annual salary.
</P>
<P>
"The reason we spent so much on decorating the bathroom is that
we think it is as important as the kitchen for our daily lives,"
Zhou explained.
</P>
<P>
"A well-decorated kitchen serves as a major index of the
improved standard of living of the residents," a man named Huang
added.
</P>
<P>
Expensive bathroom fixtures have become a priority for local
residents in their plans for redoing their apartments, and
statistics show that a total floor space of nine million sq m of
housing will be completed annually over the next few years. As a
result, per-capita living space will increase from seven sq m to
10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
