<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Trade Thriving in Border Town (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bank of China has already opened a branch in Moscow and an
office in Khabarovsk, to help transactions that require a letter
of credit and to help keep people from breaking their contracts.
</P>
<P>
The overhaul of companies involved in large-scale border
trading is one of the measures local authorities are using to
improve border trade. More than 1,120 companies that lacked the
proper qualifications for one reason or another were shut down,
said a local official in charge of trade.
</P>
<P>
Those with a sound business practices, on the other hand, have
established direct trade ties with Russian companies, and 90
percent of their contracts are honored.
</P>
<P>
Suifenhe has built a 5,700-sq-m joint inspection building,
where inspectors, commodities inspection personnel, and customs
officers check the flow of travelers and goods through the
Suifenhe port of entry.
</P>
<P>
Computers have been installed in the inspection room, where it
takes traders just a few seconds to get through entry and exit
formalities. The border inspection officers have simplified 32
procedures to facilitate border trade.
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor Qin, the town has invested over 900 million
yuan in its transport and telecommunications infrastructure in
recent years to help the border trade.
</P>
<P>
A law office opened recently in the town to deal exclusively
with problems involving foreigners. The office is in contact with
a Russian law office in Vladivostok and can mediate Sino-Russian
trade conflicts with them.
</P>
<P>
The Suifenhe branch of the China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade has also established contacts with
counterparts in Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
It is through the efforts of local authorities and
organizations such as these that Suifenhe can handle one million
tons of cargo and 500,000 persons each year.
</P>
<P>
"With the improvement of basic facilities and the
standardization of Sino-Russian border trade, I believe we traders
will have better business opportunities in the future," said Li
Fu, a Chinese businessman who has been involved in Sino-Russian
border trade for a long time and who now resides in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
