<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 07:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Trade Thriving in Border Town (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Although the border town of
Suifenhe is struggling through the sub-zero temperatures of
northeast China's winter, Chinese and Russian traders find it
fairly easy to work up a sweat just by making deals.
</P>
<P>
It is not uncommon to see Russians lugging parcels and bundles
to the check-in counter for international trains, carrying Chinese
garments and light industrial products back to Russia, where they
are in great demand.
</P>
<P>
Forty-two-year-old Ludmila has been doing business this way for
years. She's impressed with the changes she's seen at the border,
and recalls when the border trade craze first hit the area in
1991, and quality of goods began to be a problem for consumers and
quality control officers both.
</P>
<P>
"Now, everything I wear, from underwear to overcoat to shoes,
is made in China, and all are of good quality," the Russian
businesswoman explained.
</P>
<P>
Credit for this should be given to the local government. Qin
Yude, mayor of the border town, told the press that a special
commission that cracked down on fake or low-quality products was
established in 1992, and local authorities have not received a
single complaint about quality since the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the commodities inspection bureau downtown, staff members
are busy checking goods carried through by tourists. Some of the
Russians seem a bit reluctant to have their bags opened and
rummaged through.
</P>
<P>
"It'll do you no good," says one agent."We must check on the
quality of goods before we let them through."
</P>
<P>
The majority of fake or low-quality goods used to be allowed to
slip across the border by means of this "tourist" trade.
</P>
<P>
Today, both the local officials and run-of-the-mill traders are
well aware of the importance of gearing even border to the
international market to encourage healthy growth.
</P>
<P>
In a savings bank near the town's biggest border trade market,
a Russian woman is exchanging money. The Vladivostok woman
explained, "Since this bank opened, I come here to exchange money
whenever I need to. Exchange rates here are the same as those on
the international market, which makes me feel secure."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
