<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 06:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Law Helps Fujian Improve Labor-Management Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Several employees of a joint
venture in Fujian Province recently turned down a job offer with
another company of an additional 100 yuan (12 U.S.dollars) in
salary, saying, "I hate to part with the company because it's been
so good to us."
</P>
<P>
With profits increasing at an annual rate of 30 percent, the
enterprise has not only set up its own trade union as provided for
by the Labor Law, but has also set up a committee of deputies to
see that all staff members have access to discussions and
consultations on internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
A large percentage of Fujian's 17,712 foreign-funded ventures
have similar labor-management relations thanks to the Labor Law.
</P>
<P>
The first labor law in China was adopted on July 5, 1994 by the
National People's Congress Standing Committee and went into force
on January 1 of last year.
</P>
<P>
Its stipulations cover promotions, contracts, working hours,
time off, vacations, salary, on-the-job safety, women and
children's rights, vocational training, labor disputes, and other
legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Before the Labor Law was adopted, fewer than 5 percent of
Fujian's joint ventures and 17 percent of the employees had labor
contracts. To make matters worse, some contracts were clear
infringements on the rights and interests of workers.
</P>
<P>
To date, 4,794 joint ventures and 530,000 employees in the
province have labor contracts, or 90 and 88 percent of the total
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Labor Law became effective, many foreign-funded
ventures in the province have taken their own steps to improve
labor saftey and the welfare of workers, adding greatly to the
cohesiveness of the enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 06:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council of Europe Steps up Anti-Corruption Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Europe
Wednesday approved a program aimed at preventing and curbing the
trend of widespread corruption in the European Union and its
member states in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The program was approved following the arrest on January 5 in
Belgium of two former high-ranking council officials for
embezzling large sums of money.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, cases involving fraud and embezzlement
have increased rapidly in the EU, with 4,168 cases of malpractice
discovered in 1994. The number of cases involving 1.34 billion
U.S. dollars, or 1.2 percent of the EU's total 1994 budget,
represented a 64 percent increase over 1993.
</P>
<P>
Thus, anti-corruption has become one of the major tasks for the
council and the EU member states to protect the financial
interests of the European organization.
</P>
<P>
Imperfect supervision systems, the lack of coordination in laws
among the member states and the economic integration of the EU
are reportedly blamed for the rise of malpractices.
</P>
<P>
The council of Europe plans to further perfect the legal
systems of the member states and strengthen supervision over the
problem.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the EU plans to computerize by the year 1998 all
customs supervising the transportation of cargoes and strengthen
management over the import and export of cigarettes, textile and
oil-bearing products and beef.
</P>
<P>
The council also called for closer cooperation between the
European Union and its member states and for better judicial
cooperation so as to deal blows at criminal activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 06:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expels Record Number of Criminal Aliens Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States expelled a
record 31,500 criminal aliens during 1995 compared with 30,000 in
1994, Attorney General Janet Reno said here today.
</P>
<P>
The number could be even higher because December's data is
incomplete due to the partial shutdowns of the federal government
caused by Republican and Democrat dispute over a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
Reno said last year 87 million U.S. dollars were allocated to
prisons in 44 states and the District of Columbia to help pay the
prison costs of aliens in prison.
</P>
<P>
California claimed its state alone spent 400 million dollars a
year imprisoning alien criminals and called for more federal
financial aid. Justice Department figures show that California has
more than 18,000 of the estimated 37,000 imprisoned aliens.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has requested 300 million dollars
in federal aid for the program's second year, but the Justice
Department budget has been caught up in the dispute between
President Clinton and Congress over budget cutting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
