<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 06:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blueprint Heralds Economic Growth for Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, February 1 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
blueprinted its ambitious economic growth to turn itself into a
more prosperous region on the western side of the Taiwan Straits
in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Overall economic strength of the coastal province will be close
to that of moderately developed countries when the program takes
effect.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2020, Fujian's GDP is expected to reach 2.4
trillion yuan, accounting for seven percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Per capita GDP will come to 56,000 yuan, and the ratio of
urbanized area is to be enlarged to 65 percent. An estimated 60
billion U.S. dollars are to be used in building key projects and
the total export value will climb to 130 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The plans also paint a rosy picture for local residents as per
capita annual income of urban dwellers soars to 39,000 yuan, while
farmers' real income jumps to 18,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
This is an astronomical figure compared with the annual net
income of 4,300 yuan for local urbanites and farmer's 2,000 yuan
at present.
</P>
<P>
A local economist cites many reasons for the possibility of
this ambitious program, among which are the fact that the province
has completed an initial stage of industrialization and its rapid
economic growth has placed it out in front both in overall growth
and per capita share of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The next 25 years will be a period of vigorous development and
a timetable has been set for a three-stage development.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, which begins this year and ends in the year
2000, will lay a solid foundation for an economic take-off.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, provincial GDP will climb to 261.6 billion yuan with
an annual growth rate of 14 percent. Pillar industries will grow
rapidly, industrial structure will be improved, obstacles to
market operations are to be removed and a more thorough legal
system for the free flow of cargo, technical personnel, funds and
technology will be in place.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, from 2000 to 2010, will be a period of
high-speed development. In the end, its GDP will be 3.2 times the
figure in 2000, standing at 849.4 billion yuan. More modern
infrastructure will be built, six inter-provincial railways will
be operating, and regional financial, commercial, trade,
scientific, and cultural centers will be formed. The economy and
trade growth of Fujian and Taiwan will be closely integrated.
</P>
<P>
The third phase, from 2010 to 2020, is a crucial period. Fujian
will become the first developed area in China to have a GDP going
up to 2.4 trillion yuan. It will develop into a leading
manufacturing, commercial, trade, and financial center in the
Asia-Pacific region. A Taiwan Straits Economic Development Zone
will be formed to complement the integrated economic and trade
development between Fujian and Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 05:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Treaty with India Result of National  Consensus: Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The recent treaty on a border
river development between Nepal and India came out as a result of
national consensus among all major political parties in Nepal, the
Nepali government said.
</P>
<P>
An agreement reached between national political parties last
week on water resources became the foundation for the treaty,
which was initialed earlier this week during Indian Minister for
External Affairs Pranab Mukerjee's visit to Nepal, the Ministry of
Water Resources said in a press release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal-India treaty on the integrated development of
Mahakali river, Nepal's western border river with India, resolved
the controversial Tanakpur issue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the Mahakali treaty, Nepal could receive a supply of
1,000 cusecs of irrigation water in the wet season and 300 cusecs
in the dry season from India's Tanakpur hydropower and irrigation
project as well as 70 million kilowatt-hours of power every year
freely.
</P>
<P>
The new treaty would replace the 1991 Tanakpur treaty between
Nepal and India, which was not ratified by the Nepalese parliament
because opposition parties believed it did not provide enough
benefits for Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 treaty, signed by the then prime minister Girija
Prasad Koirala while visiting India, allowed India to use a small
lot of Nepalese territory to build a barrage for its Tanakpur
project, which has began generating electricity in July, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The new Nepal-India treaty would also serve as a guiding
principle to implement future projects on the Mahakali river, on
which the Tanakpur project was located.
</P>
<P>
It also provided for the constitution of a joint Mahakali river
commission between the two countries which will inspect,
coordinate, monitor and seek solutions to problems regarding
implementation of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, expected to be signed formally during Prime
Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba's visit to India later this month,
will be valid for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
Last week parliament speaker Ram Chandra Poudel called an
all-party meeting where political party leaders reached consensus
on the Tanakpur project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 05:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Child Worker School Set Up in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The first school for child
workers has opened in Dhaka to provide non-formal education to
children who, until recently, worked in garment factories in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony of the school was held Wednesday
under a memorandum of understanding signed last July 4 by
Bangladeshi garment manufacturers and the International Labor
Organization and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) with
an aim to eliminate child labor in the country.
</P>
<P>
The school, to be run by the Bangladesh Rural Advancement
Committee (BRAC), represents the first of about 500 educational
centers to be set up in urban areas to absorb the entire
population of child workers in the country's garment industry.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by international agencies,
there were 10,547 underaged workers in some 891 garment factories
in Dhaka, Narayanganj, Chittagong and Khulna. But the number of
child workers in the garment sector may be much more than that
because the total number of enlisted factories are 2,152 in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
