<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 05:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Launch Economic Packages to Boost Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 31 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany simultaneously
unveiled a broad range of economic stimulus measures on Tuesday to
reverse the economic slowdown and rising unemployment in their
countries.
</P>
<P>
Bonn proposed a broad 50-point "action program for investment
and jobs," including tax breaks and other business incentives,
plus cuts in social welfare spending to encourage enterprise,
boost growth and cut unemployment by half.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for aid for setting up new businesses, cuts in
corporate taxes, abolition of wealth and capital gains taxes, and
lower spending on early-retirement pensions, unemployment benefit
and care for the sick.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the tax system between 1997 and 2000 is designed to
help create two million new jobs, halving the current unemployment
figure of four million.
</P>
<P>
Germany's unemployment rate is set to hit 10 per cent this
year, the highest level since the end of World War II. Growth,
which slowed dramatically to 1.9 per cent in 1995, is expected to
slump further to 1.5 per cent this year.
</P>
<P>
France, which is also facing a slowdown in economic growth this
year to under 2 per cent, sought to boost consumption and
investment through narrow tax measures and cutting the interest
rate on the widely popular tax-free "Livret A" savings accounts by
a full percentage point, to 3.5 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to boost spending included tax cuts for people
buying big-ticket items like cars and incentives to buy rental
properties.
</P>
<P>
French Economics Minister Jean Arthuis said there had been
"consultation" between the two nations on developing their
respective plans, but "each side decided on the measures
corresponding to its specific situation."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Germany had decided on steps "for the medium
term", whereas France was taking "support measures" designed to
have an immediate effect on consumption and the housing sector.
</P>
<P>
"The plans are very different," said German Finance Minister
Theo Waigel, who spoke of "close cooperation" over the timing of
the announcements.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's packages were widely applauded by both nations'
business circles but trade union reaction was mainly negative,
seeing the measures as largely weighted in favor of employers.
</P>
<P>
The stimulus measures came amid continuing concern over whether
the European Union, of which France and Germany form the powerful
axis, will be ready for economic and monetary union (EMU) by the
1999 deadline set by the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, budget deficits of countries joining the
single currency must not be more than 3 per cent of GDP by
1997. But France's deficit is likely to be 4.5 per cent this year
and Germany's 3.5 per cent.
</P>
<P>
However, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and French Prime
Minister Alain Juppe have insisted that they will meet the
treaty's criteria for joining a single currency, by 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
