<HEADLINE> Syrian-Israeli Peace Talks End With "Significant Advance" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Syrian and Israeli
delegations ended their week-long peace talks today at the Wye
Plantation conference center on the Eastern Shore of Maryland with
"significant advance" on key issues.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Syrian, Israeli and U.S. delegations in the
talks, U.S. special Middle East envoy Dennis Ross issued a
statement at the end of the talks, saying Syrian and Israeli
negotiators "clarified each side's views and needs."
</P>
<P>
"All participants in this session agreed that it had
significantly advanced the discussion of key issues in a future
peace treaty," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said that there were still some
differences of substance or perspective on security arrangements
to follow a proposed Israeli withdrawal on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
"During the course of the discussions, ideas for dealing with
some of the differences were presented by both sides and will be
referred to leaderships in Israel and Syria for consideration,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, the third round since Syria and Israel resumed
their negotiations in December 1995, began on Wednesday last week.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher plans to visit
Damascus and Jerusalem next week to discuss the results of the
talks and assess the next step with the leaders of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement described the talks as a "solid basis" for the
Christopher's trip, his 17th shuttle to the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
