<HEADLINE> Colombian Congress Discusses Investigation Into President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's House of
Representatives today discussed whether it will re-open
congressional investigation into charges that President Ernesto
Samper got drug money for his election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The local press said a congressional commission in charge of the
inquiry will decide on whether to re-open its probe on the
basis of new evidence the prosecutor general's office will submit.
</P>
<P>
The commission suspended its investigation last December 14.
</P>
<P>
But the prosecutor general's office said it has received new
declarations in addition to those presented last year by former
campaign treasurer Santiago Medinas and Fernando Botero, who
helped Samper win presidential elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the commission will ask Prosecutor General
Alfonso Valdivieso to send the new evidence as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Botero, who is also a former defense minister, claimed that he
has proof that President Samper, contrary to what he says, had
detailed knowledge that the Cali cartel drug barons were involved
in his election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives is expected to re-open the case on
the basis of a report from the commission. Then it will decide
whether it will bring charges against President Samper before the
Senate further decides whether impeachment proceedings will be
initiated against him.
</P>
<P>
In the event that the evidence proves the president has committed
crimes, the Senate will request the Supreme Court of Justice to
put him on trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
