<HEADLINE> Poland's GDP Up Seven Percent in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Poland's economy grew seven
percent in 1995, bringing the country's gross domestic product
back up to its 1989 level after six years of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production rose 10 per cent while agricultural
production jumped 20 per cent, with a harvest of 25.6 million tons
of grain, the Polish Central Statistics Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
Poland's economy went through a difficult period after the
government introduced radical economic reforms in 1989. Inflation
and unemployment soared, but wages failed to keep up with price
rises. Since 1989, food prices have gone up 29 times while the
price of basic goods has risen 79 times.
</P>
<P>
However, as the economy has recovered since 1993, economic
growth has led to an improvement in people's living standards and
in the health of the national budget. Inflation has fallen from 37
per cent in 1993 but was still 27.8 per cent last year and
unemployment was 14.9 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The government has set a target of 17 per cent inflation this
year, with a slow-down in GDP growth from 1995's 7 per cent to 5.5
per cent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
