<HEADLINE> Ex-Monk Sentenced to Death for Killing Tourist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A former monk has been
sentenced to death by a Thai local court for murdering a female
British tourist last December in a temple in Kanchanaburi
province, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was handed down by the Kanchanaburi provincial
court on Wednesday, one day after Yodchat Suaphu, 21, confessed
that he had killed Briton Johanne Masheder, 23, when she resisted
a robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today said that Yodchat was also charged with
attempted rape, robbery and trying to conceal and destroy the
victim's body.
</P>
<P>
The court also ruled that Yodchat's death sentence cannot be
commuted to life as his case has shocked the public, damaged
Buddhism and tarnished the country's reputation.
</P>
<P>
The court said that Yodchat had been in jail before, but he did
not correct his behavior and repeatedly committed serious crimes
even while in the Monkhood.
</P>
<P>
The death sentence for him is necessary to set an example, the
court added.
</P>
<P>
Yodchat was defrocked after he was arrested on January 14 when
the decomposed and partly burnt body of the British tourist was
found in a cave in Khao Poon temple and her belongings, including
her passport, were found in his room.
</P>
<P>
Yodchat will soon be taken to Bang Kwang prison in Nonthaburi
province where convicts sentenced to die are put on death row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
