<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai-Israeli Trade Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Prospects are improving for
Thai exports to Israel now as Israel has established a Thai import
promotion program, according to state-run Krung Thai Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has set up an export guarantee fund that
is expected to increase bilateral trade every year, the bank says
in a research report.
</P>
<P>
Israel has also set a goal of doubling two-way trade with
Thailand over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Thailand still has a trade deficit with Israel. Last year,
Israel's exports to Thailand totaled 6.25 billion baht (250
million US dollars), while its import from Thailand amounted to
3.75 billion baht (150 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Major items Israel imported from Thailand included gems and
jewelry, rice, processed seafood, computers and accessories,
canned fruit, rubber-based products, footwear and parts, and
plastic resin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
