<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 03:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Elderly Tenants Hit Harder by Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand superannuitants
renting houses were hit harder by inflation in the quarter ending
last December than those living in their own houses, showed
figures released by Statistics New Zealand today.
</P>
<P>
Home rents went up higher for superannuitants than for other
consumers, according to the December quarter Superannuitants Price
Index (SPI).
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said rents rose 0.9 percent on average
for all New Zealand households in the quarter, but 1.2 percent for
superannuitant households.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the inflation index for superannuitant households
living in rented accommodation rose 0.8 percent in the quarter
following a one percent hike in the September quarter. This left
the annual increase rate at 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest increase was driven mainly by higher house and flat
rentals, while higher prices for newspapers and some fruit and
vegetables also contributed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
