<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 03:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> b d k BC-China-Shanghai-Foreign Lawsuits Sino-Foreign Lawsuits Being Settled More Quickly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of
sino-foreign business disputes have emerged in Shanghai, China's
largest metropolis, and departments are speeding up efforts to
resolve them in a shorter period of time.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases resolved last year was 225, a rise of 23.6
percent over 1994, with 13 cases involving intellectual property
rights and 27 about foreign trade contracts.
</P>
<P>
International economic criminal activities and some countries'
protection policies are partly to blame for the rise in the number
of lawsuits, which can be divided into four categories: common
economic disputes, anti-dumping disputes, administrative disputes,
and international trade.
</P>
<P>
More than ten cases of international trade fraud, involving
tens of thousands of US dollars, have emerged in recent years.
</P>
<P>
As many as 93 suits about regional economic regulations have
been worked out since 1990, and are having an important impact on
sino-foreign economic disputes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
