<HEADLINE> Panamanian Assembly Approves Anti-monopoly Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian assembly has
approved an anti-monopoly bill which the opposition said will harm
local producers by opening the market to big powers.
</P>
<P>
Assembly leader Carlos Alvarado declared that the bill will
benefit Panamanians since competition will be encouraged and the
prices of goods in the "basket of basic necessities" will drop.
</P>
<P>
The anti-monopoly bill was approved Tuesday by a vote of 38-8
with three abstentions. The opposition insisted that the bill
would leave local producers unprotected because it will open the
market to big powers.
</P>
<P>
The bill foresees the creation of several courts: two municipal
and three circuit courts and one superior court that will regulate
the juridical part with measures to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
The law also stipulates that toxic medications and foods that
can cause harm to people must be labeled in Spanish. 
</P>
