<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 03:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: NZ Effort to Repay Debt Rewarded  (by Chen Jinjun) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's commitment to
repay its foreign debt has been rewarded by the international
credit rating agency Standard and Poor's which upgraded NZ's
rating by a notch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based agency announced last night that it had
upgraded the New Zealand government's long-term foreign debt
rating from AA to AA-plus, the highest ranking enjoyed by the
country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Standard and Poor's said the upgrade reflects NZ's prudent
budget and monetary policies which have led to improved balance of
payments flexibility and a sharp fall in the government's net
debt burden.
</P>
<P>
This is the second upgrade for the country from the agency in
13 months. The last one came in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government recorded an operating surplus in the
1993/94 fiscal year, the first in 17 years. Since then, the
financial situation has been continuing to improve, with the
surplus increasing to 2.6 billion NZ dollars (1.7 billion US
dollars) in the first five months of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the better government finance, the government has
repeatedly made it clear that the surplus will be first used to
repay its debt, primarily the foreign currency debt to avoid the
losses caused by foreign exchange rate fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
The government's total debt stood at 47.6 billion dollars in
March 1994, among which 20 billion were held in foreign
currencies. Thanks to debt repayment efforts in the past year and
more, it fell to 30.8 billion dollars at the start of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Bill Birch announced last June that the
government's intention is to cut the current debt level which
accounts for 33.6 percent of the GDP to 18.9 billion dollars or
18.7 percent of the GDP in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
As for the foreign currency debt, economists have predicted
that they will be reduced to zero this calendar year.
</P>
<P>
With AA-plus rating, NZ is now only one level below the top AAA
grade enjoyed by some countries like the United States, Germany
and Japan, and has leapt above its Tasman neighbor Australia.
</P>
<P>
A country's credit rating affects the interest rate paid for
its overseas borrowings and an one notch up will cut about
one-fifth percentage point in the interest rate.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation of a higher rating will also have overseas
investors demanding a smaller risk premium for investing in NZ.
</P>
<P>
However, Standard and Poor's said that NZ will remain stable
despite this year's general elections. It believes that "the key
elements -- fiscal discipline, the Reserve Bank's commitment to
price stability, and the structural reforms creating a more
internationally competitive economy -- will be pursued with few
substantive changes regardless of the outcome of the elections."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
