<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Police Detain Occupiers of Foreign Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan riot police
detained early this morning all the university students who
occupied the Foreign Ministry on Tuesday, a Foreign Ministry
communique said today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 107 students, including 13 females, were taken into
custody by police and they will be tried in courts, said Nicaraguan
Deputy Interior Minister Frank Cesar, who described the occupation
as "criminal."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the police rescued from the building about
100 hostages, including Foreign Minister Ernesto Leal.
</P>
<P>
The students occupied the ministry to press their demand for
more funds for state universities. They also held hostage some 200
people working there and ambassadors of the Philippines, Pakistan,
Bolivia and Canada, who were there to present their credentials,
</P>
<P>
But they released the 100 or so female employees and the two
Asian ambassadors after hours of dialogue with Foreign
Minister Leal.
</P>
<P>
The police met with resistance during the rescue operation, the
communique said. However, it did not say whether there were any
casualties in the operation, which began at 03:30 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The police seized 27 mortar launchers and about 500 homemade
mortars from the students, who stormed into the Foreign Ministry
on Tuesday, demanding an emergency session of the National
Assembly (the parliament) to reopen budget talks on increasing
funding for universities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
