<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Scarcity Problem Alleviated in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Water projects across Shaanxi
Province in northwest China during the Eighth-Five Year Plan
(1991-1995) provided drinking water for 2.64 million people and
410,000 head of livestock.
</P>
<P>
The province's per capita water resources amount to only half
the country's standard level, meaning that it is difficult to
supply drinking water to the 32 million rural residents, more than
40 percent of whom live in areas where water is scarce.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the local government has stuck to a policy of
raising funds from as many sources as possible to solve the
problem, and has used 284 million yuan (34.2 million US dollars)
for the projects in the past five years, with more than 60
million yuan of that raised by the people themselves.
</P>
<P>
It has also sought assistance abroad. From 1992 to the end of
last year, it received funds from the UN Children's Fund totalling
870,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
It used the funds for water supply and environmental health
projects in five counties, providing relief to 210,000 people.
</P>
<P>
At present, as many as 9.77 million people and 1.6 million head
of livestock have been provided with sufficient drinking
water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
