<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Russia and four other CIS
nations have urged the opposing factions in Tajikistan to solve
the country's internal crisis peacefully by political means.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique, the countries hoped that the current
peace talks between the Tajik government and the opposition would
make a breakthrough and called on both parties to honour the
September 1994 Teheran cease-fire agreement, the Itar-Tass News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said the CIS peacekeeping unit will extend
its mission until June 30 this year, as agreed at the recent CIS
summit in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The current peace talks are part of the fifth round of a
U.N. peace process to end a three-year conflict in the central
Asian state.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan, a mountain state of 5.7 million people bordering
Afghanistan, has been plagued by unrest since 1992 after a bloody
civil war in which Islamic forces were driven out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Tensions heightened following the murder of the country's
highest Muslim leader 10 days ago and the flare-up of armed
conflicts in southern and western Tajikistan which threatened to
disrupt the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
