<HEADLINE> Mexico Criticizes U.S. Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican embassy in the
United States today strongly criticized a U.S. bill to link
U.S. financial aid to Mexico with its efforts to crack down on
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican embassy described the bill initiated by senators
Diane Feinstein and Alfonse D'Amato as harmful to the cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The embassy also repeated the Mexican government's rejection of a
proposal made by the two U.S. senators that U.S. police be allowed
to enter Mexican territory as part of their anti-drugs activities,
saying it violated Mexico's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Mexican senators Eloy Cantu Segovia and Rodolfo Becerril
Straffon also denounced the proposals.
</P>
<P>
Becerril Straffon, chairman of the Mexican senate trade
committee, criticized the two U.S. lawmakers for violating
Mexico's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He said that notorious drug traffickers are being arrested
constantly in Colombia, Bolivia and Mexico but not in the United
States which is an "insatiable market for drugs." 
</P>
