<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patient Suffering from Radiation Sickness Survives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese worker who touched a
radioactive metal chain was hospitalized with serious radiation
sickness, but was said to be in stable condition, "Beijing Youth
Daily" reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that this is the first case of a person being
injured by long-term exposure to radiation and doctors are still
not certain about possible effects in the future, such as leukemia.
</P>
<P>
The worker, Song Xuewen, 20, found a 15-cm metal chain at a
construction site in northeast China's Jilin Province on the
morning of January 5.
</P>
<P>
He looked the beautiful object over and pocketed it. What he
did not know, until he started vomiting repeatedly and his left
hand and right leg started aching and he had to see a doctor in
the afternoon, was that the chain was actually made of iridium
192, brought in a week ago by air to be used in detecting metal
flaws.
</P>
<P>
The paper did not say why the radioactive object was left at
the site or why local authorities did not warn people about it.
</P>
<P>
"Song's condition was more serious than we imagined, but it is
stable now," said Wang Guilin, head of the surgeons who had to
perform an amputation at Beijing's No. 307 Military Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Wang said it will depend on the patient's physical condition
whether he will be able to avoid radiation-related illnesses, such
as leukemia, cataracts, and sterility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Gold Producer's Output Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China's largest gold producer, in
Zhaoyuan City in east China's Shandong Province, mined 15 tons of
gold in 1995, a local official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The city invested 53.58 million yuan in prospecting during the
Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-95), said Wang Deyuan,
secretary of the Zhaoyuan Municipal Committee of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
The city's proven ore reserves totalled 9.64 million tons,
which included 543,600 tons of metallic ore.
</P>
<P>
Applications of modern science and technology have helped raise
daily ore mining capacity from 7,000 tons in 1990 to today's
11,500 tons, Wang said. 
</P>
