<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Legislators Criticize U.S. Senators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican congress today
condemned U.S. senators who they accused of trying to disqualify
Mexico from receiving financial aid.
</P>
<P>
All parties criticized plans by U.S. senators Dianne Feinstein
and Alfonse D'Amato to link financial aid to Mexico's fight
against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
During a session of congress, lawmakers for the National Action
Party (PAN), the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), the
Democratic Revolutionary Party (PRD) and the Labor Party (PT)
criticized their threat to deny certification of Mexico's war
against drugs. A denial would imply Mexico was not doing enough and
would mean a stop to financial aid.
</P>
<P>
Democrat senator Feinstein and Republican D'Amato also want to
stop bilateral agreements with Mexico unless the country meets 10
requirements linked mainly to the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Mexican legislators said that the
U.S. senators based their argument on a supposed lack of action to
combat drug trafficking. They added that the attitude of
U.S. legislators will harm the relations between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
They said it is unacceptable that Mexico is being used in an
internal electoral battle in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican congress accepts that "we have problems but solving
them is the exclusive responsibility of Mexicans and of the
political forces that, with their pluralistic outlook, their
ideological diversity, and their electoral battle, are searching
for programs that will come up with better solutions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
