<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Manned Magnetic-Suspension Train Passes Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A four-ton manned
magnetic-suspension train passed ministerial-level evaluation on
Monday at Southwest China Jiaotong University, according to the
overseas edition of the "People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper says that the approval means that land
transportation technology in China is on a par with international
standards.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the test also said that the success of the train
shows that China had solved key technological problems of
stability of magnetic suspension, which provides a basis for
further research.
</P>
<P>
The magnetic-suspension train has many advantages over
traditional trains such as pollution-free, energy-saving operation.
</P>
<P>
China began research on magnetic suspension technology in the
1980s and made the first train at Southwest China Jiaotong
University in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
China is one of only a few countries - Germany, Japan, France,
Russia, and Britain - that have this technology and have applied
it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
