<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xie Jun Draws with Polgar in Second Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAEN, Spain, January 31 (Xinhua/OANA) -- Women's world champion
Xie Jun of China drew with Hungarian challenger Zsuzsa Polgar to
take the lead in the world chess championship here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Xie, who played the whites, suggested the draws after her 17th
move and was promptly agreed by Polgar, bringing her score to 1.5
points against Polgar's 0.5.
</P>
<P>
Xie initiated the 97-minute game with the e2-e4 move for her
familiar Ruy Lopez opening.
</P>
<P>
After Polgar's 13th move (rook f8-e8), Xie deliberately put
ahead her bishop (f1-b5) in an attempt to complicate the situation
and force her opponent to consume more time in consideration.
</P>
<P>
It seemed that Xie's move did shock Polgar a little bit, who
spent nearly one hour more than Xie in Tuesday's opening game.
</P>
<P>
After three further moves, Xie proposed a draw and Polgar,
whose spirit appeared to be dented after Tuesday's loss, agreed
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The two will have a day's rest on Thursday before resuming
competition on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the 16-game championship, Xie needs only eight points to
keep her crown, while challenger Polgar has to score 8.5 points to
wrest the title.
</P>
<P>
Xie dethroned Maya Chiburdanidze of Georgia to take the world
title in 1991 and beat another Georgian Nana Ioseliani to retain
her crown in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
