<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, World's No. 1 in Marine Cultivation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China has become the world's
largest cultivator of marine products with the world's largest
output, according to "China Ocean News".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a statistical report by the International
Association for Regional Marine Fishing as saying that China's sea
farming output topped three million tons in 1994 and is estimated
to be over 3.3 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The report says that the great increase in China is mainly due
to breakthroughs in three major fields: kelp cultivation, prawn
factory-scale breeding and cultivation, and scallop cultivation,
with technology developed for mass production.
</P>
<P>
According to another report by the World Fishing Association,
total output in the world topped 101 million tons between November
1994 and October last year, with fresh water cultivation
developing more quickly than sea water cultivation. In Europe,
the U.S. and Mexican bays, the cultivation of rare and valuable
species of fish is developing more quickly, while in Asia and the
Pacific ring, the raising of traditional species is developing
more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The volume of marine fishing has at the same time declined,
showing that protection of fish resources in maritime areas has
come to be effective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960201.0239 </DOCNO>
