<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Stadium Needs Steel Reinforcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic Stadium worth of
169 million U.S. dollars, requested structure reinforcement in its
steel segments, said the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games
(ACOG).
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Wednesday, ACOG said the recommendation was
made by Weidlinger Associates Inc, a structural engineering firm
hired by the Atlanta Stadium Design Team.
</P>
<P>
"Modifications include stiffening and reinforcement of
structural steel members and to the structural steel connections
as necessary," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, the modifications would not affect the schedule for
completing the 85,000-seat stadium, ACOG said.
</P>
<P>
Last March, one construction worker was killed and two injured
when a cantilever collapsed from a 45-meter tower.
</P>
<P>
The Stadium will eventually become the home for the baseball
team of Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
