<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges Early Solution of Black Sea Fleet Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, Ukraine, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov today appealed to his Ukrainian
counterpart for an early solution of the Black Sea Fleet issue.
</P>
<P>
He told a joint press conference held with Ukrainian Foreign
Minister Gennady Udovenko that his country still hopes to solve
the fleet issue prior to Boris Yeltsin's visit to Kiev.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian foreign minister said at the press conference
that it should be a parallel process to prepare Yeltsin's visit
and to deal with the fleet issue.
</P>
<P>
"The fleet issue should not become an obstacle to Yeltsin's
visit," Udovenko stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine and Russia reached an agreement in principle last June
on the division of the Black Sea Fleet of the former Soviet Union,
under which Ukraine allowed the Russian Navy to be based in
Sevastopol, the headquarters of the Ukrainian Navy.
</P>
<P>
When asked if there will be any modification to the
Russian-Ukrainian treaty of friendship, cooperation and
partnership initialed last year, Udovenko said Ukraine is prepared
to sign the document without any change.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister, however, said the two countries
had only reached agreement on the treaty but did not initial it.
</P>
<P>
On February 8 last year, Evgeni Marchuk and Oleg Soskovets,
first deputy prime ministers of Ukraine and Russia, reportedly
initialed the treaty in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was designed to enter into force when Russian
President Yeltsin and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma signed it
during Yeltsin's visit.
</P>
<P>
But Yeltsin's scheduled visit to Ukraine was postponed by his
heart problem.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian foreign minister also said his country shares a
similar view with Russia regarding the eastward enlargement by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
He said the NATO should take into consideration the national
security of Ukraine while expanding eastward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
