<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murdoch Plans To Launch Global News Channel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian-born media
tycoon Rupert Murdoch unveiled a plan to launch a satellite
television channel that beams news to most parts of the world in
two years.
</P>
<P>
Murdoch's News Corp will establish a world-wide channel that
carries the news programs of its US-based Fox television station.
</P>
<P>
He said that the global 24-hour news channel would cost less
than 100 million US dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The News Corp has already got full coverage of Asia through its
Hong Kong subsidiary Star TV. It has also been beaming news to
Europe through Sky TV, an European satellite TV station owned by
Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its operation in North America, the News Corp
has gained access to the South America satellite TV market by
extending its coverage all over the continent within this year.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be covering a great deal more than two-thirds of the
world where we'll be able to put or serve news as well as other
channels," today's Australian Financial Review quoted Murdoch as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Murdoch has put Roger Ailes in charge of the proposed news
channel. Ailes shifted to Murdoch's ranks last week from the
presidency of CNBC, the business news network under the US
television giant NBC.
</P>
<P>
The News Corp will also provide news on the Internet. But
Murdoch declined to reveal who would be the partner in the group's
on-line service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
