<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Cotton Output To Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia's cotton crop for
the year 1996-97 is expected to reach a new record due to good
rains in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Cherry, general manager of Cotton Trading Corporation,
said that the 1996-97 harvest could equal or exceed the previous
record of 2.2 million bales in 1992-93, the Australian Financial
Review reported today.
</P>
<P>
It will be 50 percent higher than the recent crop, which is due
to be harvested in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
The recent harvest was affected by lack of irrigation water at
time of planting and damages by heavy rains recently.
</P>
<P>
But Cherry said that recent down pours had filled many
near-empty public dams and guaranteed abundant supply of
irrigation water for the crop to be sowed next spring.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was confident to lock in good prices for the
crops for 1997 and 1998, because the United States' cotton
production has been affected by natural disasters this year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian crop for 1995-96 is estimated at 1.565 million
bales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
