<DATE_TIME> 1996-01-36 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Greater Recognition of Black Women's  Contributions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
in his annual black history month proclamation Wednesday, urged
greater recognition for the achievements of black women.
</P>
<P>
He said black women "have fought extraordinary battles for
social, economic and political empowerment."
</P>
<P>
"The voices of African-American women have called attention to
the twin burdens of racism and sexism and have invited listeners
to discover the richness of traditions kept alive in back kitchens
and workrooms," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has repeatedly addressed the wide gulf between blacks'
and whites' perceptions of American society over the months.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "identified this for himself as a task of leadership
that he wanted to meet, because a president can address those
divisions in our society that keep people apart," White House
Spokesman Mike McCurry said. "He will continue to do that."
</P>
<P>
Clinton most recently spoke about race in Houston, McCurry
said, during the funeral of Barbara Jordan, the first black woman
elected to Congress from a Southern state.
</P>
<P>
Clinton again recalled Jordan's legacy in Wednesday's
proclamation, noting her observation that blacks were not counted
as citizens when the Constitution was written in 1787, yet they
persevered and ultimately gained full rights.
</P>
<P>
Clinton encouraged teachers to craft lessons around the works
of black women.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said, the Clinton administration continues working on a
formal strategy for addressing racial concerns through policies
and practices "that provide opportunity for people of color and
that reward those efforts to bring people together to find common
ground, that bridges some of the gaps that do exist."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
