<HEADLINE> Chirac, Clinton to Have Long Agenda for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and French President Jacques Chirac will meet on Thursday for a
long agenda of talks, the White House announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that Clinton
and Chirac will focus their discussions on nuclear
non-proliferation, Bosnia, trade and other economic issues at
their summit meeting at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Chirac arrived here this afternoon for a two-day state visit,
the first of the kind by a French president in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
"The large issues are non-proliferation, particularly the
French and Russian efforts...to pull together the nuclear safety
summit in Moscow in April," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac announced on Monday that France had ended its nuclear
testing after six underground explosions. The Clinton
administration immediately issued a statement, welcoming the French
president's announcement.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Clinton, Chirac is also expected to
propose a new NATO partnership.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who has move France back towards NATO's military
organization after a 30-year break since coming to power last May,
said in a recent interview with the Washington Post that he
considered the Atlantic Alliance "a permanent cornerstone of
French security."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the time has come to revamp the Atlantic
Alliance and create a more equal partnership with the United
States in which a uniting Europe will assume greater
responsibility for its own security.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will speak to a joint session of the U.S. Senate and
House of Representatives to call for more U.S. foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Europe, with about the same size economy as the United States,
reportedly gave three times as much to developing countries in
1995, totaling 31 billion U.S. dollars compared with less than 9
billion U.S. dollars from the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
