<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Unveils Land Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The South African
department of land affairs today released a comprehensive package
of land reform proposals aimed at wiping out the legacy of
apartheid and creating security of tenure for citizens in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The proposals, which include a grant of up to 15000 rand
(about 4100 US dollars) per household to help disadvantaged
groups buy land, were contained in a green paper, or discussion
document.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the document in Cape Town, Land Affairs Minister
Derek Hanekom said he hoped to have a white paper, or final
policy document after a further round of consultations with
provincial ministers of land affairs.
</P>
<P>
"A central concern in making these proposals has been to
translate a broad commitment to social justice and alleviation of
poverty, into a set of concrete programmes, legislation and
procedures," said Hanekom.
</P>
<P>
Major issues facing the department after the release of the
document would include rationalizing the chaotic land
administration of the former homelands, where day-to-day
administration and record keeping had broken down, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
However, the document said the government would not give
priority to people or groups who participated in land invasions,
nor would threats of land invasions be rewarded by special
treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
