<DATE_TIME> 1996-02-01 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radiation in Dimitrovgrad Normal, Moscow Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1(Xinhua) -- The Russian Atomic Energy
Ministry today described as normal the radiation level in the city
of Dimitrovgrad, about 750 kilometers southeast of Moscow, where
an accident occurred on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the radiation level on the territory of a sanitary
zone of a research institute of nuclear reactors in the city does
not exceed the permissible level and measures 10-20 micro Roentgen
per hour.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry admitted, in the contaminated area of
approximately 200 square meters the radiation level exceeds the
norm by 10-20 times, reaching 250 micro Roentgen per hour.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred at 11:15 Moscow time (08:15 GMT) on
Wednesday, when a safety precaution valve was activated, reducing
pressure in the reactor which was stopped, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported, adding that a steam-like mixture was discharged
into the atmosphere measuring 100 millicurie, which contaminated
part of the territory of the research complex.
</P>
<P>
Managers of the research complex said that none of the
personnel had been hurt and that there was no immediate threat to
their health. The accident as preliminary assessed as level "one"
on a seven-point international scale of accidents at nuclear power
stations.
</P>
<P>
The after-effects of the accident are being eliminated by the
staff of the research institute responsible for clean-up in
incidents of radioactive contamination, Itar-Tass said. At
present, operations to bury the contaminated snow are being
completed, and the reactor was expected to be put into operation
in a few hours, the news agency noted tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
