<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabian Ship Sinks off Cyprus Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A Saudi Arabian-flagged ship
sank off the coast of the Turkish-controlled northern part of
Cyprus, according to the Cyprus News Agency (CNA) today.
</P>
<P>
The 10 crew members of the ship, which set sail from Limassol
port in Cyprus southern government-controlled areas on Tuesday
heading for Burgas port in Bulgaria, were rescued, the CNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Cyprus Ports Authority (CPA) was quoted as
saying that the ship Seal Vanamar set sail on Tuesday afternoon
from Limassol and was destined for Burgas port, Bulgaria,
according to the official documents.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot reports said the ship sank off the eastern
tip of the island while sailing for Mersin, southern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to the CPA spokesman, with a capacity of 1,018 tons,
the ship was carrying 500 tons of steel loaded in Ukraine and 19
containers with cigarettes. However, the spokesman did not give
any other details of the ship and the cause of the sinking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
